#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "astrophoto denoise"
msgstr "riduci rumore foto astronomiche"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Remove image noise while preserving structure. \n"
msgstr "Rimuove il rumore immagine preservando struttura. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is accomplished by averaging each pixel with some surrounding pixels in the image. The weight of such a pixel in the averaging process depends on the similarity of its neighborhood with the neighborhood of the pixel being denoised. A patch with a defined size is used to measure that similarity. \n"
msgstr ""
"Questo viene ottenuto mediando ciascun pixel assieme con i pixel che lo "
"circondano. Il peso di tale pixel nel processo di media dipende dalla "
"somiglianza tra il suo \"vicinato\" e il \"vicinato\" del pixel per il quale "
"si sta riducendo il rumore. Per misurare tale similarità si usa un'area di "
"dimensione definite. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As denoising is a resource-intensive process, it slows down pixelpipe processing significantly. Consider activating this module late in your workflow.\n"
msgstr ""
"Siccome la riduzione del rumore è un processo che consuma molte risorse "
"rallenta l'elaborazione della pixelpipe in maniera significante. Considera "
"di ritardare l'attivazione di questo modulo verso la fine del tuo flusso di "
"lavoro.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"patch size\n"
": The radius of the patch used for similarity evaluation.\n"
msgstr ""
"Dimensioni campione\n"
": Il raggio del campione usato per la valutazione della similarità\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": The strength of the denoising.\n"
msgstr ""
"intensità\n"
": La forza della riduzione del rumore\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"luma\n"
": The amount of denoising to apply to luma. Select carefully in order not to lose too much structure.\n"
msgstr ""
"luminanza\n"
": L'ammontare di riduzione di rumore da applicare alla luminosità. Impostare "
"con accortezza per non perdere troppa struttura.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/astrophoto-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"chroma\n"
": The amount of denoising to apply to chroma. You can be much more aggressive with this parameter.\n"
msgstr ""
"crominanza\n"
": L'ammontare di riduzione del rumore da applicare alla crominanza. Con "
"questo parametro puoi essere più aggressivo.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "base curve"
msgstr "curva base"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate the in-camera JPEG by applying a characteristic base curve to the image.\n"
msgstr ""
"Simula il JPEG prodotto dalle fotocamera applicando una curva caratteristica "
"di base all'immagine.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable comes with a number of base curve presets that attempt to mimic the curves of various camera manufacturers. These presets are automatically applied according to the manufacturer ID found in the image's Exif data. Camera-specific base curve presets are also available for some camera models. \n"
msgstr ""
"darktable fornisce una serie di preset per la curva base che tentano di "
"imitare le curve di vari produttori di fotocamera. Questi preset vengono "
"applicati automaticamente a seconda dell'ID del produttore che si trova nei "
"dati Exif dell'immagine. Sono anche disponibili alcuni preset specifici per "
"fotocamera, solo per alcuni modelli. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module will be enabled by default if [preferences > processing > auto-apply pixel workflow defaults](../../preferences-settings/processing.md) is set to \"display-referred\".  A second option in the preferences dialog allows you to choose whether darktable should attempt to apply a camera-specific base curve (if found) or the generic manufacturer one.\n"
msgstr ""
"Questo modulo verrà abilitato di default se [preferenze > elaborazione > "
"applica automaticamente i valori predefiniti per il flusso di lavoro sui "
"pixel](../../preferences-settings/processing.md) è impostato su \"riferito "
"alla scena\". Una seconda opzione nella finestra delle preferenze ti "
"permette di scegliere se darktable dovrebbe tentare di applicare una curva "
"base specifica per la fotocamera (se c'è) o quella generica per il "
"produttore.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_Please refer to the [curves](../../darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md) section for more details about how to modify curves including the **scale for graph** and **preserve colors** controls._\n"
msgstr ""
"_Si prega di rifarsi alla sezione [curve](../../darkroom/processing-modules/"
"curves.md) per maggiori dettagli su come modificare le curve, inclusi i "
"parametri **scala del grafico** e **preserva colori**.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fusion\n"
": Trigger the exposure fusion feature (see [this Wikipedia article](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposure_Fusion)). This feature allows you to merge the image with one or two copies of itself after applying the current base curve and boosting its exposure by a selected number of EV units. The resulting image is thus a combination of two or three different exposures of the original image. \n"
": Use this feature to compress the dynamic range of extremely underexposed images or for true HDR input. For best results, use the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module to apply a suitable adjustment for correctly exposed highlights.\n"
msgstr ""
"fusione\n"
": Abilita la funzionalità di fusione esposizione (leggi [questo articolo "
"Wikipedia (EN)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposure_Fusion)). Questa "
"funzionalità ti permette di fondere l'immagine con una o due copie di se "
"stessa applicando la curva base corrente e aumentando la sua esposizione di "
"un numero predeterminato di EV. L'immagine risultante è quindi la "
"combinazione di due o tre differenti esposizioni della stessa immagine "
"originale.\n"
": Usa questa funzionalità per comprimere la gamma dinamica per immagini "
"estremamente sottoesposte o per input HDR veri. Per i migliori risultati, "
"usa il modulo [_esposizione_](./exposure.md) per ottenere delle alteluci "
"correttamente esposte.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure shift (fusion)\n"
": The exposure difference between the merged images in EV units (default 1). This slider is only visible if the _exposure fusion_ feature is activated.\n"
msgstr ""
"cambio esposizione (fusione)\n"
": La differenza, espressa in unità EV, in termini di esposizione tra le "
"immagini in fusione (predefinito 1 EV). Questo selettore scorrevole è "
"visibile se la _fusione esposizione_ è attiva.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure bias (fusion)\n"
": Determines how the multiple exposures are computed. With a bias of 1 (the default), the image is fused with overexposed copies of itself. With a bias of -1, it is fused with underexposed copies. A bias of 0 attempts to preserve the overall lightness of the image by combining both over- and under-exposed copies of the image. This slider is only visible if the _exposure fusion_ feature is activated.\n"
msgstr ""
"compensazione esposizione (fusione)\n"
": Stabilisce come le esposizioni multiple vengono calcolate. Con una "
"compensazione di 1 (valore predefinito), l'immagine viene fusa con copie "
"sovraesposte di sé stessa. Con una compensazione di -1 verrà fusa con copie "
"sottoesposte. Con una compensazione di 0, si tenterà di preservare la "
"luminosità generale dell'immagine combinando copie dell'immagine sia sovra "
"che sotto esposte. Questo selettore scorrevole è visibile se la _fusione "
"esposizione_ è attiva.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "censorize"
msgstr "censura"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Degrade parts of the image in an aesthetically pleasing way, in order to anonymize people/objects or hide body parts.\n"
msgstr ""
"Degrada parte dell'immagine in maniera gradevole a vedersi, al fin di "
"anonimizzare persone/oggetti o nascondere parti del corpo.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Censorize works in linear RGB color space to apply a physically-accurate gaussian blur and gaussian luminance noise.\n"
msgstr ""
"Il modulo censura lavora nello spazio colore RGB lineare per applicare una "
"sfocatura gaussiana e un rumore di luminosità gaussiano che sia fisicamente "
"accurato.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Aside from anonymization, this module can also be used for a wide range of creative purposes, for example:\n"
msgstr ""
"Oltre all'anonimizzazione, questo modulo può essere usato per vari scopi "
"creativi, ad esempio:\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Combine a simple blur with a multiply [blend mode](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md) to create a realistic bloom (Orton effect).\n"
msgstr ""
"Combinare una semplice sfocatura con la [modalità di fusione](../../darkroom/"
"masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md) moltiplica per creare un effetto di "
"sovraesposizione realistica (_blooming_, effetto Orton).\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Combine a simple blur with a subtract blending mode and low opacity to create an [unsharp mask](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unsharp_masking), similar to the [sharpen](./sharpen.md) module but in an RGB scene-referred space.\n"
msgstr ""
"Combinare una semplice sfocatura con una modalità di fusione in sottrazione "
"e bassa opacità per creare una [maschera di nitidezza (EN)](https://en."
"wikipedia.org/wiki/Unsharp_masking), similarmente al modulo "
"[nitidezza](./sharpen.md) ma in uno spazio colore RGB riferito alla scena.\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Add noise to create artificial grain.\n"
msgstr "Aggiungere rumore per creare una grana artificiale.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The anonymizing methods provided by this module are not forensically safe in order to favor aesthetics. Some forensic techniques may still be able to reconstruct the censorized content based on its structure, especially for simple shapes and text (e.g. license plates, street numbers).\n"
msgstr ""
"**Nota:** Il metodo di anonimizzazione fornito da questo modulo, per "
"favorire l'estetica, non è sicuro dal punto di vista forense. Alcune "
"tecniche forensi potrebbero essere in grado di ricostruire il contenuto "
"censurato nella sua struttura, soprattutto per forme semplici e testi (es: "
"targhe, numeri delle vie).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If forensically safe anonymization is required, the only way to achieve this is to paint the surfaces with a solid color. \n"
msgstr ""
"Se è necessaria un'anonimizzazione che sia sicura dal punto di vista "
"forense, l'unico modo per ottenerla è quella di riempire l'area con una "
"tinta unita. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**The darktable team does not accept responsibility for poorly anonymized pictures leading to the identification of individuals or personal property.**\n"
msgstr ""
"**Il team di darktable non accetta responsabilità per immagini non "
"sufficientemente anonimizzate che portino all'identificazione di individui o "
"proprietà personali**\n"

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/diffuse.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "workflow"
msgstr "flusso di lavoro"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You are advised to leave the module's controls at their default values while you [mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) the areas of the image that you wish to censorize, in order that the details of the image remain visible.\n"
msgstr ""
"Ti consigliamo di lasciare i parametri del modulo ai loro valori predefiniti "
"quando [mascheri](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) l'area "
"dell'immagine che vuoi censurare, in modo tale che i dettagli dell'immagine "
"rimangano visibili.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input blur radius\n"
": The strength of the first pass of the gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""
"raggio di sfocatura\n"
": L'intensità del primo passaggio della sfumatura gaussiana\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pixellation radius\n"
": The size of the \"big pixels\" created after the first pass of gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""
"raggio di pixellizzazione\n"
": La dimension dei \"pixel grandi\" creati dopo il primo passaggio di "
"sfocatura gaussiana\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"output blur radius\n"
": The strength of the second pass of the gaussian blur, applied after the pixellation.\n"
msgstr ""
"raggio di sfocatura in usicta\n"
": L'intensità del secondo passaggio di sfumatura gaussiana, applicata dopo "
"la pixellizzazione.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"noise level\n"
": The strength (standard deviation) of the luminance gaussian noise applied after the second pass of the gaussian blur. Adding noise can fake details in the blurred regions and make content detection more difficult for artificial intelligence algorithms.\n"
msgstr ""
"livello di rumore\n"
": La forza (deviazione standard) del rumore della luminosità gaussiana "
"applicata dopo il secondo passaggio della sfumatura gaussiana. Aggiungere "
"rumore può falsare i dettagli delle aree sfocate e rendere più difficile "
"l'identificazione dei contenuti, da parte algoritmi di intelligenza "
"artificiale.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "chromatic aberrations"
msgstr "aberrazioni cromatiche"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Correct chromatic aberrations.\n"
msgstr "Corregge le aberrazioni cromatiche.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In contrast to the [_raw chromatic aberrations_](./raw-chromatic-aberrations.md) module, this module does not require raw data as input.\n"
msgstr ""
"Al contrario del modulo [_aberrazioni cromatiche del raw_](./raw-chromatic-"
"aberrations.md), questo modulo non richiede dati raw in ingresso.\n"

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "workflow "
msgstr "flusso di lavoro "

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To obtain the best result, you are advised to proceed as follows:\n"
"1. Attenuate the chromatic aberrations as much as possible in the [_lens correction_](./lens-correction.md) module using the TCA sliders.\n"
"2. Increase the strength slider in this module to better see its effect.\n"
"3. Increase the radius until the chromatic aberrations disappear. If this is insufficient, try enabling the \"very large chromatic aberrations\" setting.\n"
"4. Choose the guide that gives the best result in term of sharpness and artifacts.\n"
"5. Reduce the strength to avoid washing out the colors too much.\n"
msgstr ""
"Per ottenere i migliori risultati, ti consigliamo di procedere come segue:\n"
"1. Attenuare le aberrazioni cromatiche quanto più possibile nel modulo ["
"_correzione obiettivo_](./lens-correction.md) usando il selettore scorrevole "
"per il TCA.\n"
"2. Aumentare l'intensità in quel modulo per vedere meglio il suo effetto.\n"
"3. Incrementare il raggio finché le aberrazioni cromatiche scompaiono. Se "
"questo non è abbastanza, prova ad abilitare l'impostazione \"Aberrazione "
"cromatica molto ampia\".\n"
"4. Scegliere la guida con cui si ottiene il massimo risultato in termini di "
"nitidezza e artefatti.\n"
"5. Ridurre l'intensità per evitare di sbiadire troppo i colori.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For more complicated cases you could also try the following:\n"
"- Use several instances with different correction modes -- for example, a first instance in \"brighten only\" mode, and a second in \"darken only\" mode.\n"
"- Use several instances with low strength to correct the chromatic aberrations a little at a time without degrading colors too much.\n"
"- Use the module with parametric or drawn masks.\n"
"- Use RGB red, green and blue blend modes to restrict the effect to a particular channel.\n"
msgstr ""
"Per i casi più complicati puoi anche provare come segue:\n"
"- Usa più di un'istanza con diverse modalità di correzione -- per esempio "
"una prima istanza in modalità \"schiarisci solamente\" e una seconda in "
"\"scurisci solamente\".\n"
"- Usa più di un'istanza con ridotta intensità per correggere le aberrazioni "
"cromatiche poco alla volta, senza degradare troppo i colori.\n"
"- Usa il modulo con una maschera disegnata o parametrica.\n"
"- Usa le modalità di fusione RGB rosso, verde e blu per restringere "
"l'effetto ad un canale in particolare.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"guide\n"
": The color channel that will be used as a reference for the correction.\n"
msgstr ""
"guida\n"
": Il canale colore che verrà usato come riferimento per la correzione.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radius\n"
": The radius of the effect. Increase until chromatic aberrations are eliminated. This is the most important slider of the module.\n"
msgstr ""
"raggio\n"
": Il raggio dell'effetto. Incrementare fino a quando le aberrazioni "
"cromatiche vengono eliminate. Questo è il parametro più importante del "
"modulo.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": This slider acts as a safeguard and can help to preserve colorful areas that do not suffer from chromatic aberrations. Increase for stronger correction, decrease for stronger preservation.\n"
msgstr ""
"intensità\n"
": Questo selettore scorrevole agisce da salvaguardia e può aiutare a "
"preservare le aree molto colorate che non soffrono di aberrazioni "
"cromatiche. Incrementare per una correzione più aggressiva, decrementare per "
"maggior preservazione.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"correction mode\n"
": Allows you to restrict the effect to brighten or darken pixels only. For full control, this can be used in combination with R, G, B blend modes and multiples instances.\n"
msgstr ""
"modo correzione\n"
": ti permette di limitare l'effetto solo allo schiarimento o allo scurimento "
"dei pixel. Per avere controllo totale, questo può essere usato assieme alle "
"modalità di fusione R, G e B (rosso, verde e blu) con le istanze multiple.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"very large chromatic aberrations\n"
": Makes the algorithm iterative to help in reducing very large chromatic aberrations.\n"
msgstr ""
"aberrazione cromatica molto ampia\n"
": Rende iterativo l'algoritmo per aiutare a ridurre aberrazioni cromatiche "
"molto ampie.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-contrast.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color contrast"
msgstr "contrasto colore"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-contrast.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A simplified control for changing the contrast or separation of colors between the green/magenta and blue/yellow axes in Lab color space. Higher values increase color contrast, lower values decrease it.\n"
msgstr ""
"Un controllo semplificato per cambiare il contrasto o la separazione dei "
"colori sulle assi verde/magenta e blu/giallo nello spazio color Lab. Valori "
"più alti incrementano il contrasto, più bassi lo diminuiscono.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-contrast.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"green-magenta contrast\n"
": Change the green-magenta color contrast. This is equivalent to raising or lowering the steepness of the a\\* curve in Lab. Lower values desaturate greens and magenta, while higher values increase their saturation.\n"
msgstr ""
"contrasto verde-magenta\n"
": Cambia il contrasto colore verde-magenta. Questo è equivalente "
"all'aumentare o ridurre la pendenza della curva a\\* in Lab. Valori più "
"bassi desaturano il verde e il magenta, mentre valori più alti ne "
"incrementano la saturazione.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-contrast.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue-yellow contrast\n"
": Change the blue-yellow color contrast. This is equivalent to raising or lowering the steepness of the b\\* curve in Lab. Lower values desaturate blues and yellows, while higher values increase their saturation.\n"
msgstr ""
"contrasto blu-giallo\n"
": Cambia il contrasto color blu-giallo. Questo è equivalente ad aumentare o "
"ridurre la pendenza della curva b\\* in Lab. Valori più bassi desaturano i "
"blu e i gialli, mentre valori più alti ne aumentano la saturazione.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color look up table"
msgstr "tabella ricerca colore"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A generic color look up table implemented in Lab space. \n"
msgstr ""
"Una tabella di ricerca colore generica, implementata nello spazio colore "
"Lab. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The input to this module is a list of source and target points and the complete mapping is interpolated using splines. The resulting look up tables (LUTs) are editable by hand and can be created using the darktable-chart utility to match given input (such as hald-cluts and RAW/JPEG with in-camera processing pairs). See [using darktable-chart](../../special-topics/darktable-chart/_index.md) for details.\n"
msgstr ""
"L'input di questo modulo è una lista di punti di origine e destinazione, e "
"la mappatura completa viene interpolata usando spline. La tabella di ricerca "
"(LUT, _Look Up Table_) è modificabile a mano e può essere creata usando il "
"programma darktable-chart per abbinare l'input fornito (come hald-cluts e "
"RAW/JPEG con processo di accoppiamento in-camera). Controlla [usare "
"darktable-chart](../../special-topics/darktable-chart/_index.md) per i "
"dettagli.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color board\n"
": The color board grid shows a list of colored patches. The colors of the patches are the source points. The target color of the selected patch is shown as offsets which are controlled by sliders beneath the color board. An outline is drawn around patches that have been altered (where the source and target colors differ). \n"
msgstr ""
"lavagna dei colori\n"
": La lavagna dei colori mostra una grigli di caselle colorate. I colori "
"delle caselle sono i punti origine. Il colore destinazione di una casella "
"selezionata è mostrata come compensazione controllata dai selettori a "
"scorrimento sotto la lavagna colori. Sulle caselle che sono state alterate ("
"dove i colori di origine e destinazione sono diversi) viene disegnato un "
"contorno. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Click a patch to select it, or use the combo box or color picker. The currently-selected patch is marked with a white square, and its number is displayed in the combo box below.\n"
msgstr ""
": Fai click su una casella per selezionarla, o usa il menù a tendina o il "
"selettore colore. La casella selezionata al momento è evidenziata con un "
"quadrato bianco, e il suo numero viene mostrato nel menù a tendina più in "
"basso.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": By default, the module will load the 24 patches of a classic color checker and initialise the mapping to identity (no change to the image). Configurations with more than 24 patches are shown in a 7x7 grid.\n"
msgstr ""
": Di default, il modulo caricherà le 24 caselle dei colori classici in un "
"ColorChecker e inizializza la matrice alla sua identità (nessun cambiamento "
"nell'immagine). Le configurazioni con più di 24 caselle vengono mostrate in "
"una griglia 7x7.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interaction\n"
": To modify the color mapping, you can change the source and target colors, though the main use is to change the target colors.\n"
msgstr ""
"interazione\n"
": Per modificare la mappatura dei colori, puoi cambiare sia il colore "
"origine e di destinazione, sebbene l'uso principale è di cambiare i colori "
"di destinazione.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Start with an appropriate palette of source colors (either from the presets menu or from a style you have downloaded). You can then change the lightness (L), green-red (a), blue-yellow (b), or saturation \\(c\\) of the patches' target values with the sliders.\n"
msgstr ""
": Inizia con una palette appropriata di colori origine (sia dal menù dei "
"preset o da uno stile che hai scaricato). Puoi quindi usare i selettori "
"scorrevoli per cambiare i valori di luminosità (L), verde-rosso (a), blu-"
"giallo (b) o saturazione (c) del colore di destinazione della casella.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": To change the source color of a patch you can select a new color from your image by using the color picker and Shift+click on the patch you want to replace.\n"
msgstr ""
": Per cambiare il colore di origine di una casella, puoi selezionare un "
"nuovo colore dalla tua immagine utilizzando il selettore colore facendo "
"Maiusc+click sulla casella che vuoi rimpiazzare.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-look-up-table.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Double-click a patch to reset it; Right-click a patch to delete it; Shift+click on empty space to add a new patch (with the currently picked color as the source).\n"
msgstr ""
": Doppio click su una casella per reimpostarla; Click di destro sulla "
"casella per eliminarla; Maiusc+click su uno spazio vuoto per aggiungere una "
"nuova casella (con il colore attualmente selezionato come origine).\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color reconstruction"
msgstr "ricostruzione colore"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Recover color information in blown-out highlights.\n"
msgstr "Recuperare informazioni sui colori nelle alte luci tagliate.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Due to the nature of digital sensors, overexposed highlights lack valid color information. Most frequently they appear neutral white or exhibit some color cast, depending on what other image processing steps are involved. This module can be used to “heal” overexposed highlights by replacing their colors with better fitting ones. The module acts on pixels whose luminance exceeds a user-defined threshold. Replacement colors are taken from neighboring pixels. Both the spatial distance and the luminance distance (range) are taken into account for color selection.\n"
msgstr ""
"A causa della natura dei sensori digitali, le alte luci sovraesposte mancano "
"di informazioni valide sui colori. Molto spesso appaiono in bianco neutrale "
"o mostrano una dominante colorata, a seconda di quali altri passi di "
"elaborazione dell'immagine sono coinvolti. Questo modulo può essere usato "
"per \"guarire\" le alte luci sovraesposte rimpiazzando il loro colore con "
"uno più appropriato. Il modulo agisce sui pixel la cui luminanza eccede una "
"soglia definita dall'utente. I colori da usare come rimpiazzo vengono presi "
"dai pixel vicini. Per la selezione del colore vengono prese in "
"considerazione sia la distanzia spaziale che di luminanza.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Due to a limitation of the underlying algorithm, reconstructed colors may sometimes be displayed incorrectly if you zoom into the image in the darkroom view. If this happens you might observe a magenta shift in highlight areas close to high contrast edges, or you might see colorless highlight areas when used alongside the “reconstruct color” method of the [_highlight reconstruction_](./highlight-reconstruction.md) module. These artifacts only influence on-screen image display -- the final output remains unaffected. It is recommended that you finetune the parameters of this module only when viewing the fully zoomed-out image.\n"
msgstr ""
"A causa di una limitazione dell'algoritmo interno, certe volte i colori "
"ricostruiti possono essere visualizzati in maniera errata se si zooma dentro "
"l'immagine nella Camera Oscura. Se succede potresti osservare un dominante "
"magenta nelle aree di alte luci, vicino ai bordi con contrasto alto, o "
"potresti vedere aree di alte luci senza colori quando usato assieme al "
"metodo \"ricostruisci colore\" del modulo [_recupero alteluci_](./highlight-"
"reconstruction.md). Questi artefatti interessano soltanto la visualizzazione "
"dell'immagine a schermo -- il risultato finale rimane inalterato. Si "
"raccomanda di mettere a punto i parametri di questo modulo solo quando si "
"sta guardando l'intera l'immagine a schermo (non zoomata).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Note that similar functionality is also available in the _reconstruct_ tab of the [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md#reconstruct) module.\n"
msgstr ""
"Notare che una funzionalità simile è anche disponibile nella scheda "
"_ricostruisci_ del modulo [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md#reconstruct).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": The color reconstruction module replaces the color of all target pixels having luminance values above this threshold. Only pixels with luminance values below the threshold are taken as valid source pixels for replacement colors. Setting this parameter too high will cause the module to have no effect on any pixels. Setting it too low will minimize the “pool” of replacement colors -- if no suitable colors are available, the original colors are retained. This parameter therefore exhibits a “sweet spot” characteristic with an optimum setting depending on the individual image.\n"
msgstr ""
"soglia\n"
": Il modulo di ricostruzione colore sostituisce il colore di tutti i pixel "
"che hanno valori di luminanza maggiori di questa soglia. Solo i pixel con "
"valori di luminanza sotto la soglia vengono presi come pixel origine per la "
"sostituzione colore. Impostare questo parametro troppo alto farà in modo che "
"il modulo non abbia effetto su nessun pixel. Impostarlo troppo basso ridurrà "
"il \"gruppo\" dei colori sostitutivi -- se non sono disponibili colori "
"adatti verrà mantenuto il colore originale. Questo parametro ha quindi un "
"\"punto giusto\" con un valore ottimale in base all'immagine in particolare."
"\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"spatial extent\n"
": The spatial distance that source pixels may have from target pixels in order for them to contribute to color replacement. Higher values cause ever more distant pixels to contribute. This increases the chance of finding a replacement color but can make the replacement color less well suited for the reconstruction.\n"
msgstr ""
"estensione spaziale\n"
": La distanza spaziale che può separare il pixel di origine dal pixel di "
"destinazione affinché possa contribuire alla sostituzione colore. Valori più "
"alti faranno in modo che contribuiscano anche pixel ancora più distanti. "
"Questo incrementa le possibilità di trovare un colore sostitutivo ma "
"potrebbe renderlo meno appropriato per la ricostruzione.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"range extent\n"
": The range difference (in luminance) that source pixels may have from target pixels in order for them to contribute to color replacement. Higher values cause more pixels to contribute even if their luminance differs more strongly from the target pixels. This again increases the chance of finding a replacement color but at the same time increases the risk of unfitting colors creeping in.\n"
msgstr ""
"intervallo di estensione\n"
": La differenza di intervallo (tra luminanze) che il pixel origine può avere "
"dal pixel destinazione affinché contribuisca alla sostituzione colore. "
"Valori più alti faranno in modo che contribuiranno più pixel, anche se la "
"loro luminanza differisca più ampiamente dai pixel di destinazione. Questo "
"nuovamente aumenta le probabilità di trovare un colore sostitutivo ma allo "
"stesso tempo aumenta il rischio che si intrometta un colore non appropriato."
"\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"precedence\n"
": This combobox defines whether certain replacement colors shall take precedence over others as follows:\n"
msgstr ""
"precedenza\n"
": questo menù a tendina stabilisce se determinati colori sostitutivi debbano "
"avere la precedenza sul altri, come segue:\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _off_ (default): All pixels contribute equally\n"
": - _saturated colors_: Pixels contribute according to their chromaticity -- the more highly-saturated a color, the more it contributes\n"
": - _hue_: Give precedence to a specific hue (see below)\n"
msgstr ""
": - _nessuno_ (predefinito): Tutti i pixel contribuiscono equamente\n"
": - _colori saturati_: I pixel contribuiscono in base alla loro cromaticità "
"-- tanto più è saturato un colore, tanto più contribuisce.\n"
": - _tonalità_: Da la precedenza a specifiche tonalità (leggi più in basso)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": This slider is only visible if you set the _precedence_ to “hue”. It allows you to select a preferred hue for replacement colors. This only has an effect if the preferred hue is actually present within the selected spatial and range distance of the target pixels (see above). A typical use case is repairing highlights on human skin in situations where diverging colors are in close proximity (e.g. textiles or hair with a luminance close that of to skin). Setting a hue preference on skin tones prevents these other colors from creeping in.\n"
msgstr ""
"tonalità:\n"
": questo selettore scorrevole è visibile soltanto se imposti la _precedenza_ "
"a \"tonalità\". Ti permette di selezionare la tonalità preferita per il "
"colori sostitutivi. Questo ha effetto solo se la tonalità preferita è "
"davvero presente nella distanza e nell'intervallo dei pixel di destinazione ("
"vedi sopra). Un tipo caso d'uso è la correzione delle alte luci nella pelle "
"umana dove colori divergenti si avvicinano troppo (es: tessili o capelli con "
"valori di luminanza vicini a quello della pelle). Impostare la tonalità "
"preferita sul tono della pelle per evitare che altri colori si intromettano."
"\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "colorize"
msgstr "colora"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Add a solid layer of color to the image.\n"
msgstr "Aggiunge un livello di tinta unita all'immagine.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": The hue of the color layer.\n"
msgstr ""
"tonalità\n"
": La tonalità del livello colore.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": The saturation of shadow tones.\n"
msgstr ""
"saturazione\n"
": La saturazione delle ombre.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness\n"
": The lightness of the color layer.\n"
msgstr ""
"chiarezza\n"
": La luminosità del livello colore.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"source mix\n"
": Controls how the lightness of the input image is mixed with the color layer. Setting this to zero will result in a uniformly colored plane.\n"
msgstr ""
"sorgente miscelazione\n"
": Controlla quanto la luminosità dell'immagine di input sia mischiata con il "
"livello colore. Impostandolo a zero si avrà un piano colorato uniformemente."
"\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "exposure"
msgstr "esposizione"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Increase or decrease the overall brightness of an image. \n"
msgstr "Incrementa o riduce l'esposizione globale di un'immagine. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module has two modes of operation:\n"
msgstr "Questo modulo può operare in due modalità:\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"manual\n"
": Set the _exposure_, _black level_ and _clipping threshold_ manually\n"
msgstr ""
"manuale\n"
": Imposta l'_esposizione_, il _livello del nero_ e la _soglia di tosaggio_ "
"manualmente.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"automatic (RAW images only)\n"
": Use an analysis of the image's histogram to automatically set the exposure. Darktable automatically selects the exposure compensation that is required to shift the selected _percentile_ to the selected _target level_ (see definitions below). This mode is particularly useful for automatically altering a large number of images to have the same exposure. A typical use case of automatic mode is deflickering of time-lapse photographs. \n"
msgstr ""
"automatico (solo immagini RAW)\n"
": Usa l'analisi dell'istogramma dell'immagine per impostare automaticamente "
"l'esposizione. Darktable seleziona automaticamente la compensazione "
"dell'esposizione che è necessaria per spostare il _percentile_ selezionato "
"verso il _livello di destinazione_ desiderato (vedi definizioni più in basso)"
". Questo modo è particolarmente utile per modificare un gruppo di molte "
"immagini che hanno la stessa esposizione. Un tipico caso d'uso della "
"modalità automatica è per rimuovere il tremolio (\"deflickering\") nella "
"fotografia time lapse. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": Choose the mode of operation (automatic/manual).\n"
msgstr ""
"modo\n"
": Sceglie il modo operativo (automatico/manuale).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"compensate camera exposure (manual mode)\n"
": Automatically remove the camera exposure bias (taken from the image's Exif data).\n"
msgstr ""
"compensa l'esposizione delle fotocamera (modo manuale)\n"
": Rimuove automaticamente la correzione esposizione della fotocamera (presa "
"dai dati Exif dell'immagine).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure (manual mode)\n"
": Increase (move to the right) or decrease (move to the left) the exposure value (EV).\n"
msgstr ""
"esposizione (modo manuale)\n"
": Aumenta (verso destra) o riduce (verso sinistra) il valore di esposizione "
"(EV).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clipping threshold (manual mode)\n"
": Define what percentage of bright values are to be clipped in the calculation of the _exposure_ and _black level correction_. Use the color picker to sample a portion of the image to be used for this calcuation.\n"
msgstr ""
"soglia di tosaggio (modo manuale)\n"
": Stabilisce quale percentuale di valori luminosi debba essere tagliata nel "
"calcolo dell'_esposizione_ e del _livello del nero_. Usa il selettore colore "
"per campionare una porzione dell'immagine per essere usata in questo calcolo."
"\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"percentile (automatic mode)\n"
": Define a location in the histogram to use for automatic exposure correction. A percentile of 50% denotes a position in the histogram where 50% of pixel values are above and 50% of pixel values are below that exposure.\n"
msgstr ""
"percentile (modo automatico)\n"
": Stabilisce la posizione di riferimento sull'istogramma per la correzione "
"automatica dell'esposizione. Un percentile del 50% indica una posizione "
"nell'istogramma dove il 50% dei pixel è al di sopra di quella esposizione e "
"il restante 50% ne è al di sotto.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"target level (automatic mode)\n"
": Define the target level for automatic exposure correction (EV) relative to the white point of the camera.\n"
msgstr ""
"livello target (modo automatico)\n"
": Indica il livello desiderato per la correzione dell'esposizione (in EV) "
"relativo al punto di bianco della fotocamera.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"black level correction (manual and automatic modes)\n"
": Adjust the black level point to unclip negative RGB values. \n"
msgstr ""
"correzione del livello del nero (modo manuale e automatico)\n"
": Regola il punto del livello del nero per evitare che i valori RGB negativi "
"vengano tagliati. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Do not use the black level correction to add more density in blacks as this can clip near-black colors out of gamut by generating negative RGB values. This can cause problems with some modules later in the pixelpipe. Instead, use a tone mapping curve to add density to the blacks. For example, you can use the _relative black exposure_ slider on the _scene_ tab of the [filmic rgb](filmic-rgb.md#scene) module, or establish a deeper toe in the [base curve](base-curve.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""
"**Nota:** non usare la correzione livello del nero per aggiungere maggiore "
"intensità ai neri: questo può risultare in un taglio dei colori vicini al "
"nero che sono fuori dalla gamma (gamut), generando quindi valori RGB "
"negativi. Questo potrebbe generare problemi in alcuni moduli più avanti "
"nella pixelpipe. Usa invece una curva di mappatura del tono per aumentare la "
"densità dei neri. Puoi usare per esempio il selettore scorrevole "
"dell'_esposizione nero relativo_ nella scheda _scena_ del modulo [filmic rgb"
"](filmic-rgb.md#scene), o imposta una punta più profonda nel modulo [curva "
"base](base-curve.md).\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "graduated density"
msgstr "filtro graduato"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate a graduated density filter in order to correct exposure and color in a progressive manner.\n"
msgstr ""
"Simula un filtro a densità neutra graduata, in modo tale di correggere "
"l'esposizione e i colori in maniera progressiva.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A line is shown on screen allowing the position and rotation of the gradient to be modified with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""
"Sullo schermo viene visualizzata una linea che permette di modificare col "
"mouse la posizione e la rotazione del gradiente.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is known to provoke banding artifacts under certain conditions. You should consider activating the [_dithering_](./dithering.md) module to alleviate these issues.\n"
msgstr ""
"Per questo modulo è risaputo che provochi artefatti di \"banding\" in alcune "
"condizioni. Dovresti considerare l'attivazione del modulo "
"[_dithering_](./dithering.md) per alleviare il problema.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"density\n"
": Set the density of the filter (EV). A low value underexposes slightly whereas a high value creates a strong filter.\n"
msgstr ""
"densità\n"
": Imposta la densità del filtro (in EV). Un valore basso sottoespone "
"leggermente mentre un valore alto crea un filtro più intenso.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hardness\n"
": The progressiveness of the gradient. A low value creates a smooth transition, whereas a high value makes the transition more abrupt.\n"
msgstr ""
"intensità (durezza)\n"
": La progressività del gradiente. Un valore basso crea una transizione "
"dolce, mentre un valore alto rende la transizione più improvvisa.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rotation\n"
": The rotation of the filter. Negative values rotate clockwise. The rotation can also be set by dragging the end of the gradient line with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""
"rotazione\n"
": la rotazione del filtro. Valori negativi ruotano in senso orario. La "
"rotazione può essere impostata anche trascinando con il mouse la fine della "
"linea di gradiente.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": Choose a hue to add a color cast to the gradient.\n"
msgstr ""
"tonalità\n"
": Sceglie una tonalità per dare una dominante colorata al gradiente.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": The saturation of the color cast to add to the gradient (defaults to a neutral color cast of 0)\n"
msgstr ""
"saturazione\n"
": La saturazione della dominante colorata da aggiungere al gradiente ("
"predefinita ad un colore dominante neutrale di 0)\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/grain.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "grain"
msgstr "grana"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/grain.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate the grain of analog film. The grain is processed on the L channel of Lab color space.\n"
msgstr ""
"Simula la grana della pellicola analogica. La grana viene elaborata sul "
"canale L dello spazio colore Lab.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/grain.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"coarseness\n"
": The grain size, scaled to simulate an ISO number.\n"
msgstr ""
"ruvidezza\n"
": La dimensione della grana, rapportata per simulare un valore ISO.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/grain.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": The strength of the effect.\n"
msgstr ""
"intensità\n"
": L'intensità dell'effetto.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "haze removal"
msgstr "rimozione foschia"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically reduce the effect of dust and haze in the atmosphere. This module may also be employed more generally to give pictures a color boost specifically in low-contrast regions of the image.\n"
msgstr ""
"Riduce automaticamente l'effetto di polvere e foschia nell'atmosfera. Questo "
"modulo può anche essere usato più in generale per dare alle immagini un "
"accento di colore in più soprattutto nelle aree dell'immagine con basso "
"contrasto.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Haze absorbs light from objects in the scene but it is also a source of diffuse background light. The haze removal module first estimates, for each image region, the amount of haze in the scene. It then removes the diffuse background light according to its local strength and recovers the original object light.\n"
msgstr ""
"La foschia assorbe luci dagli oggetti nella scena ma è anche una sorgente di "
"luce diffusa di sfondo. Il modulo di rimozione foschia stima inizialmente, "
"per ciascuna area dell'immagine, l'ammontare di foschia nella scena. Quindi "
"rimuove la luce diffusa di sfondo in base all'intensità locale e recupera la "
"luce originale degli oggetti.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting both of the module's controls to unity maximizes the amount of haze removal but is also likely to produce some artifacts. Removing the atmospheric light entirely may render the image flat and result in an unnatural looking style. Optimal values are typically below unity and are rather image dependent, but also a matter of personal aesthetic preferences.\n"
msgstr ""
"Impostare entrambi i parametri del modulo all'unità massimizza l'effetto "
"della rimozione foschia ma è probabile che produca anche artefatti. "
"Rimuovere per intero la luce atmosferica potrebbe rendere l'immagine piatta "
"e con una luce innaturale. I valori ottimali sono tipicamente al di sotto "
"dell'unità e comunque sono dipendenti dell'immagine, ma anche una questione "
"di personali preferenze estetiche.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": The amount of haze removal. At unity, the module removes 100 percent of the detected haze up to the specified distance. Negative values increase the amount of haze in the image.\n"
msgstr ""
"intensità\n"
": L'ammontare di rimozione foschia. All'unità il modulo rimuove il 100% "
"della foschia individuata alla distanza specifica. Valori negativi "
"incrementano l'ammontare di foschia nell'immagine.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"distance\n"
": Limit the distance up to which haze is removed. For small values, haze removal is restricted to the foreground of the image. Haze is removed from the entire image if the distance parameter is set to unity. If the _strength_ is negative the distance control has no effect.\n"
msgstr ""
"distanza\n"
": Limita fino a quale distanza la foschia viene rimossa. Per valori piccoli, "
"la rimozione foschia è limitata al primo piano dell'immagine. La foschia "
"viene rimossa completamente dall'immagine se il parametro distanza è "
"impostato a uno. Se l'_intensità_ è negativa il controllo della distanza non "
"ha effetto.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "highlight reconstruction"
msgstr "recupero alteluci"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Attempt to reconstruct color information for pixels that are clipped in one or more RGB channel. \n"
msgstr ""
"Tenta la ricostruzione delle informazioni colore per i pixel che sono stati "
"tagliati in uno o più canali RGB. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If these pixels are left partially clipped it can result in unrealistic colors appearing in the image. For example pixels with both green and blue channels clipped will appear to be red without any highlight reconstruction.\n"
msgstr ""
"Se questi pixel sono rimasti parzialmente tagliati in uno o due canali, "
"possono risultare in colori non realistici nell'immagine. Per esempio, pixel "
"con i canali verde e blu entrambi tagliati, appariranno rossi senza alcun "
"recupero delle alteluci.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Three methods of reconstruction are available:\n"
msgstr "Sono disponibili tre metodi di recupero:\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clip highlights\n"
": Clamp all pixels to the white level (i.e. clip the remaining color channels). This method is most useful in cases where clipped highlights occur in naturally desaturated objects (e.g. clouds).\n"
msgstr ""
"taglio alteluci\n"
": blocca tutti i pixel al livello del bianco (es: tagliando i canali colore "
"rimanenti). Questo metodo è il più utile quando il ritaglio (\"clipping\") "
"delle alteluci avviene su oggetti desaturati di natura (es: le nuvole).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"reconstruct in LCh\n"
": Analyse each pixel with at least one clipped channel and attempt to correct the clipped pixel (in LCh color space) using the values of the other (3 for Bayer or 8 for X-Trans) pixels in the affected sensor block. The reconstructed highlights will still be monochrome, but brighter and with more detail than with “clip highlights”. This method works fairly well with a high-contrast base curve, which renders highlights desaturated. As with _clip highlights_ this method is a good option for naturally desaturated objects.\n"
msgstr ""
"ricostruisci in LCh\n"
": Analizza ciascun pixel con almeno un canale tagliato e tenta la correzione "
"del pixel ritagliato (nello spazio colore LCh) usando i valori degli altri "
"pixel nel blocco interessato nel sensore (3 altri pixel per sensori Bayer o "
"8 per sensori X-Trans). Le alteluci recuperate rimarranno monocromatiche, ma "
"più luminose e con maggiori dettagli che usando \"taglio alteluci\". Questo "
"metodo funziona correttamente con una curva base ad alto contrasto, la quale "
"produce alteluci desaturate. Come \"taglio alteluci\" questo metodo è una "
"buona opzione per oggetti desaturati di natura.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"reconstruct color\n"
": Use an algorithm that transfers color information from unclipped surroundings into the clipped highlights. This method works very well on areas with homogeneous colors and is especially useful on skin tones with smoothly fading highlights. Please note that this method can produce maze-like artifacts on highlights behind high-contrast edges, for example well-exposed fine structures in front of an overexposed background.\n"
msgstr ""
"ricostruisci colore\n"
": Usa un algoritmo che trasferisce le informazioni colore dai pixel non "
"ritagliati nelle vicinanze alle alteluci tagliate. Questo metodo funziona "
"molto meglio nelle aree con colori omogenei ed è particolarmente utile sui "
"toni della pelle con alteluci che sfumano dolcemente. Notare che questo "
"metodo può produrre artefatti \"a labirinto\" sulle alteluci dietro a bordi "
"con alto contrasto, per esempio in caso di strutture correttamente esposte "
"davanti ad uno sfondo sovraesposto.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For highlight reconstruction to be effective you need to also apply a negative EV correction in the [exposure](./exposure.md) module\n"
msgstr ""
"Per un recupero efficiente delle alteluci devi anche applicare un valore EV "
"negativo di correzione nel modulo [exposure](./exposure.md).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** When using the highlight reconstruction included with the [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md) module it may be useful to disable the _highlight reconstruction_ module so that filmic has more information to work with.\n"
msgstr ""
"**Nota:** quando si usa il recupero alteluci incluso nel modulo [_filmic rgb_"
"](./filmic-rgb.md) potrebbe essere utile disabilitare il modulo _recupero "
"alteluci_ in modo tale da lasciare a filmic maggiori informazioni con cui "
"lavorare.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"method\n"
": The method used to reconstruct highlights (see above).\n"
msgstr ""
"metodo\n"
": Il metodo usato per recuperare le alteluci (leggi sopra).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clipping threshold\n"
": Manually adjust the clipping threshold against magenta highlights. You shouldn't need to adjust this.\n"
msgstr ""
"soglia di tosaggio\n"
": Regola manualmente la soglia per il tosaggio rispetto alle alteluci "
"magenta. Non dovresti avere bisogno di regolarlo.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "hot pixels"
msgstr "pixel bruciati"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically detect and eliminate hot pixels. \n"
msgstr "Identifica ed elimina automaticamente i pixel bruciati. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hot pixels are pixels which have failed to record a light level correctly. Detected hot pixels are replaced by an average of their neighbors.\n"
msgstr ""
"I pixel bruciati sono pixel che hanno fallito a registrare la quantità di "
"luce correttamente. I pixel bruciati individuati vengono sostituiti dalla "
"media dei pixel confinanti.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": How strong a pixel's value needs to deviate from that of its neighbors to be regarded as a hot pixel.\n"
msgstr ""
"soglia\n"
": Quanto il valore di un pixel deve deviare da quelli adiacenti per essere "
"considerato come un pixel bruciato.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": The blending strength of the hot pixels with their surrounding.\n"
msgstr ""
"intensità\n"
": L'intensità con cui i pixel bruciati devono essere fusi con i pixel "
"circostanti.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"detect by 3 neighbours\n"
": Extend the detection of hot pixels -- regard a pixel as hot if a minimum of only three (instead of four) neighbor pixels deviate by more than the threshold level.\n"
msgstr ""
"determina da 3 vicini\n"
": Estende l'identificazione dei pixel bruciati -- considera un pixel come "
"bruciato se almeno tre (invece che quattro) pixel adiacenti deviano oltre il "
"livello di soglia.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mark fixed pixels\n"
": Visually mark the corrected pixels on the image and display a count of hot pixels that have been fixed.\n"
msgstr ""
"marca i pixel corretti\n"
": contrassegna visualmente sull'immagine i pixel corretti e visualizza il "
"numero dei pixel bruciati che sono stati riparati.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-black-white-point.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "raw black/white point"
msgstr "punto nero/bianco raw"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-black-white-point.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Define camera-specific black and white points. \n"
msgstr "Definisce i punti di bianco e di nero specifici per la fotocamera. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-black-white-point.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is activated automatically for all raw images. Default settings are applied for all supported cameras. Changes to the defaults are not normally required.\n"
msgstr ""
"Questo modulo si attiva automaticamente per tutte le immagini raw. Vengono "
"applicate impostazioni predefinite per le fotocamere supportate. Solitamente "
"non sono richieste modifiche al default.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-black-white-point.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"black level 0-3\n"
": The camera-specific black level of the four pixels in the RGGB Bayer pattern. Pixels with values lower than this level are not considered to contain valid data.\n"
msgstr ""
"livelli di nero 0-3\n"
": I livelli di nero specifici per la fotocamera dei quattro pixel nello "
"schema Bayer RGGB. Pixel con valori inferiori a questo livello vengono "
"considerati come non contenenti dati validi.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-black-white-point.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"white point\n"
": The camera-specific white level. All pixels with values above this are likely to be clipped and will be handled accordingly in the [_highlight reconstruction_](./highlight-reconstruction.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""
"punto di bianco\n"
": Il livello di bianco specifico per la fotocamera. Tutti i pixel con valori "
"oltre questo è probabile che vengano tagliati e verranno gestiti in base al "
"modulo [_recupero alteluci_](./highlight-reconstruction.md).\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "raw chromatic aberrations"
msgstr "aberrazioni cromatiche del raw"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Correct chromatic aberrations of raw images.\n"
msgstr "Corregge le aberrazioni cromatiche delle immagine raw.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As this module operates on non-demosaiced raw data, the underlying model assumes an uncropped photographic image as input. It is therefore likely to fail when you zoom in, as it is only able to operate on the visible portion of the image. The module will therefore be bypassed at high zoom levels, and a \"bypassed\" message will appear at the top of the module. This limitation only applies to interactive work and not to the final export. \n"
msgstr ""
"Siccome questo modulo opera sui dati raw non-demosaicizzati, il modello "
"sottostante assume che l'input sia l'immagine fotografica non ritagliata. E' "
"quindi probabile che il modulo fallisca quando si zooma, dato che è in grado "
"di operare solo sulla porzione visibile dell'immagine. Il modulo verrà "
"quindi ignorato a livelli alti di zoom e un messaggio apposito apparirà in "
"alto al modulo. Questa limitazione si applica soltanto durante la "
"lavorazione interattiva e non sull'export finale. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module currently only works for raw images recorded with a Bayer sensor (the sensor used in the majority of cameras) -- for other types of image, you should use the [_chromatic aberrations_](./chromatic-aberrations.md) module instead. \n"
msgstr ""
"Questo modulo funziona correntemente solo per immagini registrate con un "
"sensore Bayer (il sensore usato nella maggiorparte delle fotocamere) -- per "
"gli altri tipi di immagini dovresti invece usare il modulo [_aberrazioni "
"cromatiche_](./chromatic-aberrations.md). \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The module will also not apply any corrections to any photos that have been identified as monochrome (see [developing monochrome images](../../guides-tutorials/monochrome.md) for more information).\n"
msgstr ""
"Inoltre il modulo non applicherà alcuna correzione alle foto identificate "
"come monocromatiche (vedi [sviluppare immagini monocromatiche](../../guides-"
"tutorials/monochrome.md) per maggiori informazioni).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"iterations\n"
": The number of iterations. For most images, \"twice\" is sufficient, and is the default value. Occasionally, increasing this control can give better results.\n"
msgstr ""
"iterazioni\n"
": Il numero di iterazioni. Per la maggior parte delle immagini, \"due volte\""
" è sufficiente. Occasionalmente, incrementare questo parametro può fornire "
"risultati migliori.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"avoid colorshift\n"
": If the module causes purple tinting, tick this box to apply a correction.\n"
msgstr ""
"evita lo spostamento colore\n"
": Se il modulo causa una dominante viola, seleziona questa casella per "
"impostare una correzione.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "raw denoise"
msgstr "riduzione rumore raw"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Perform denoising on raw image data before it is [demosaiced](./demosaic.md). \n"
msgstr ""
"Effettua una riduzione del rumore sui dati raw dell'immagine prima che venga "
"[demosaicizzata](./demosaic.md). \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module has been ported from [dcraw](https://www.dechifro.org/dcraw/).\n"
msgstr ""
"Questo modulo è stato convertito da [dcraw](https://www.dechifro.org/dcraw/)."
"\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"noise threshold\n"
": The threshold for noise detection. Higher values lead to stronger noise removal and greater loss of image detail.\n"
msgstr ""
"soglia rumore\n"
": La soglia per l'individuazione del rumore. Valori più alti portano a una "
"riduzione del rumore più aggressiva e una maggiore perdita di dettaglio "
"nell'immagine.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"coarse/fine curves\n"
": The noise of an image is usually a combination of fine-grained and coarse-grained noise. These curves allow the image to be denoised more or less depending on the coarseness of the visible noise. The left of the curve will act on very coarse grain noise, while the right of the curve will act on very fine grain noise. \n"
msgstr ""
"curve grezzo/fine\n"
": Il rumore di un'immagine è solitamente la combinazione di rumore a grana "
"sia fine che grezza. Queste curve permettono di ridurre più o meno il rumore "
"in base alla \"ruvidezza\" del rumore visibile. La parte sinistra della "
"curva agisce sul rumore più grossolano , mentre la parte a destra agisce sul "
"rumore a grana fine. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Raising the curve will result in more smoothing, while lowering it will result in less smoothing. As an example, you can preserve very fine-grained noise by pulling down the rightmost point of the curve to the minimum value. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": If you are tackling chroma noise with a [blend mode](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md), you can raise the rightmost part of the curve quite high, as colors do not change a lot on fine grain scales. This will help especially if you see some isolated pixel left un-denoised. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": The best way to use the R, G, and B curves is to examine each of the channels in turn using the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module in gray mode, denoise that channel, and then repeat for the other channels. This way, you can take into account the fact that some channels may be noisier than others. Beware that guessing which channel is noisy without actually seeing the channels individually is not straightforward and can be counterintuitive. A pixel which is completely red may not be caused by noise on the R channel, but actually by noise on G and B channels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": See the [wavelet](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md) section for more details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "rotate pixels"
msgstr "ruota pixel"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The sensors of some cameras (such as the Fujifilm FinePix S2Pro, F700, and E550) have a diagonally oriented Bayer pattern instead of the usual orthogonal layout.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Without correction this would lead to a tilted image with black corners. This module applies the required rotation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable detects images that need correction using their Exif data and automatically activates this module where required. For other images the module always remains disabled.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-pixels.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/scale-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The module has no controls.\n"
msgstr "Il modulo non ha controlli.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/scale-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "scale pixels"
msgstr "ridimensiona pixel"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/scale-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Some cameras (such as the Nikon D1X) have rectangular instead of the usual square sensor cells. Without correction this would lead to distorted images. This module applies the required scaling.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/scale-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable detects images that need correction using their Exif data and automatically activates this module where required. For other images the module always remains disabled. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "soften"
msgstr "ammorbidisci"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Create a softened image using the [Orton effect](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orton_(photography)).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Michael Orton achieved his results on slide film by using two exposures of the same scene, one well exposed and one overexposed. He then used a darkroom technique to blend these two images into a final image where the overexposed image was blurred.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is a near-copy of Orton's analog process into the digital domain.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"size\n"
": The size of blur of the overexposed image. The bigger the size, the softer the result.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": The saturation of the overexposed image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"brightness\n"
": The brightness (EV) of the overexposed image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/soften.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mix\n"
": How the two images are mixed. 50% represents an equal mix of the well exposed and overexposed images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "surface blur"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Smooth image surfaces while preserving sharp edges using a bilateral filter. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module _can_ be used to denoise images, however you should be aware that bilateral filters are susceptible to overshoots and darktable offers much better alternatives. For example, the [_astrophoto denoise_](./astrophoto-denoise.md) module uses a non-local means denoising algorithm, and the [_denoise (profiled)_](./denoise-profiled.md) module provides a choice between non-local means and wavelet denoising algorithms. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _surface blur_ module blurs noise within the surfaces of an image by averaging pixels with their neighbors, taking into account not only their geometric distance but also their distance on the range scale (i.e. differences in their RGB values). It can be particularly useful if one RGB channel is more noisy/needs more smoothing than the others. In such a case, use the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module to examine the channels one by one, in order to set the blur intensities accordingly. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The module can also be used as a creative filter to provide interesting effects, for example to lend an image a cartoon-like appearance. When used with chrominance blending, it can also be used to even out the color of a surface (for example, to remove skin redness).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is resource-intensive and slows down pixelpipe processing significantly. You should consider activating it late in your workflow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radius\n"
": The spacial extent of the gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/surface-blur.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"red, green, blue\n"
": The blur intensity for each of the RGB channels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/unbreak-input-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "unbreak input profile"
msgstr "correzione profilo di ingresso"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/unbreak-input-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Add a correction curve to image data. This is required if you have selected certain input profiles in the [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/unbreak-input-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you decide to use an ICC profile from the camera manufacturer in the [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) module, a correction curve frequently needs to be pre-applied to image data to prevent the final output from looking too dark. This extra processing is not required if you use darktable's standard or enhanced color matrices. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/unbreak-input-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The correction curve is defined with a linear part extending from the shadows to some upper limit and a gamma curve covering mid-tones and highlights. For further information please see darktable's neighboring project [UFRaw](http://ufraw.sourceforge.net).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/unbreak-input-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linear\n"
": The upper limit for the region counted as shadows and where no gamma correction is performed. Typically values between 0.0 and 0.1 are required by the profile.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/unbreak-input-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"gamma\n"
": The gamma value required to compensate the input profile. Often the required value is 0.45 (the reciprocal of the 2.2 gamma used by some manufacturer's profiles).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "input color profile"
msgstr "profilo colore di ingresso"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Define how darktable will interpret the colors of the image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module takes the color space used by the image source (e.g. camera, scanner) and converts the pixel encodings to a standardized working color space. This means that subsequent modules in the pipeline don't need to be concerned with the specifics of the input device, and can work with and convert to/from a common working color space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Where an image has been captured in a raw file, the input color profile module will normally apply either a standard or enhanced color matrix specific for that camera model, which will be used to map the colors into the working profile color space. If color space information is embedded in the image, the _input color profile_ module will use this information when mapping the colors to the working profile color space. The user can also explicitly specify a color space for the incoming image, and can even supply a custom ICC color profile specifically made for the input device.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As part of the mapping from the input color space to the working profile space, the colors can be confined to a certain gamut using the _gamut clipping_ options, which can help to mitigate some (infrequent) color artifacts. This is also influenced by the chosen [rendering intent](../../special-topics/color-management/rendering-intent.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Note that the final color profile that will be used when exporting the image is controlled by the [_output color profile_](output-color-profile.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input profile\n"
": The profile or color matrix to apply. A number of matrices are provided along with an enhanced color matrix for some camera models. The enhanced matrices are designed to provide a look that is closer to that of the camera manufacturer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": You can also supply your own input ICC profiles and put them into `$DARKTABLE/share/darktable/color/in` or `$HOME/.config/darktable/color/in` (where `$DARKTABLE` is the darktable installation directory and `$HOME` is your home directory). One common source of ICC profiles is the software that is shipped with your camera, which often contains profiles specific to your camera model. You may need to activate the [_unbreak input profile_](./unbreak-input-profile.md) module to use your own profiles.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": If your input image is a low dynamic range file like JPEG, or a raw file in DNG format, it might already contain an embedded ICC profile, which darktable will use by default. You can restore this default by selecting “embedded icc profile”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"working profile\n"
": The working profile used by darktable's processing modules. Each module can specify an alternative space that it will work in, and this will trigger a conversion. By default darktable will use \"linear Rec2020 RGB\", which is a good choice in most cases.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"gamut clipping\n"
": Activate a color clipping mechanism. In most cases you can leave this control in its default “off” state. However, if your image shows some specific features such as highly saturated blue light sources, gamut clipping might be useful to avoid black pixel artifacts. See [possible color artifacts](../../special-topics/color-management/color-artifacts.md) for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/input-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Choose from a list of RGB profiles. Input colors with a saturation that exceeds the permissible range of the selected profile are automatically clipped to a maximum value. “linear Rec2020 RGB” and “Adobe RGB (compatible)” allow for a broader range of unclipped colors, while “sRGB” and “linear Rec709 RGB” produce a tighter clipping. Select the profile that prevents artifacts while still maintaining the highest color dynamics. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lowlight vision"
msgstr "visione luminosità scarsa"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate human lowlight vision. This module can also be used to perform a day-to-night conversion.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The idea is to calculate a [scotopic vision](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotopic_vision) image, which is perceived by the rods rather than the cones in the eyes under low light. Scotopic lightness is then mixed with photopic value (regular color image pixel) using some blending function. This module can also simulate the [Purkinje effect](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purkinje_effect) by adding some blueness to the dark parts of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module comes with several presets, which can be used to get a better idea of how the module works.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"curve\n"
": The horizontal axis represents pixel lightness from dark (left) to bright (right). The vertical axis represents the kind of vision from night vision (bottom) to day vision (top).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue\n"
": Set the blue hint in shadows (Purkinje effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/output-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "output color profile"
msgstr "profilo colore di uscita"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/output-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Manage the output profile for export and the rendering intent to be used when mapping between color spaces.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/output-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable comes with pre-defined profiles _sRGB_, _Adobe RGB_, _XYZ_ and _linear RGB_. You can provide additional profiles by placing them in `$DARKTABLE/share/darktable/color/out` and `$HOME/.config/darktable/color/out` (where `$DARKTABLE` is the darktable installation directory and `$HOME` is your home directory).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/output-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The output color profile may also be defined within the [export](../utility-modules/shared/export.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/output-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"output intent\n"
": The rendering intent for output/export. Rendering intent can only be selected when using LittleCMS2 to apply the output color profile (this can be changed in [preferences > processing](../../preferences-settings/processing.md)). If darktable's internal rendering routines are used, this option is hidden. For more details see [rendering intent](../../special-topics/color-management/rendering-intent.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/output-color-profile.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"output profile\n"
": The profile used to render colors for output/export. The profile data will be embedded into the output file (if supported by the file format) allowing other applications to correctly interpret its colors. As not all applications are aware of color profiles, the general recommendation is to stick to sRGB unless you know what you are doing and have a good reason to do otherwise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color balance"
msgstr "bilanciamento colore"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A versatile tool for adjusting the image's color balance. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module can be used to revert parasitic color casts or to enhance the visual atmosphere of an image using color grading, a popular technique in the cinema industry. For scene-referred workflow, you should consider using the improved [_color balance rgb_](./color-balance-rgb.md) module instead.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _color balance_ module allows you to shift colors selectively by luminance range (shadows, mid-tones, and highlights). It can do this using two different methods:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lift, gamma, gain\n"
": The classic method, which allows a more separated control of shadows versus highlights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"slope, offset, power\n"
": The new standard defined by the American Society of Cinematographers Color Decision List (ASC CDL) and more suited to scene-referred editing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _master_ settings affect the whole image. They are not available in _lift, gamma, gain (sRGB)_ mode. The slider ranges are limited to usual values ([50%; 150%] for saturation, [-50%; 50%] for contrast), but higher and lower values can be defined via keyboard input after right-clicking on the corresponding slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For better efficiency, in _slope, offset, power_ mode it is recommended that you set the slope first, then the offset, and finally the power, in that order. The name of the mode can be use as a mnemonic to remember the order. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The shadows parameter has a far heavier effect in _slope, offset, power_ mode than in _lift, gamma, gain_ mode. When switching from the former to the latter, you should adapt the saturation in shadows, dividing by around 10.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Although this module acts on RGB colors its location in the pixelpipe puts it into the Lab color space. Accordingly the module converts from Lab to RGB, performs its color adjustments, and then converts back to Lab.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Several presets are provided in this module to help you to better understand how it can best be used. The \"teal/orange color-grading\" preset is a very popular look in cinema and is a good showcase model. It is meant to be used with two instances combined with [masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md). The first instance will exclude skin tones and will shift neutral colors toward teal blue. The second will partially revert the first one and add more vibrance to skin tones only. Together they will create separation between subject and background. The masking and blending parameters will need to be tweaked to suit every image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Other presets provide Kodak film emulations. In this way you can recreate any film look you like using _color balance_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": _lift, gamma, gain (sRGB)_ is the legacy mode from darktable 2.4 and earlier. In this mode, the color transformations are applied in sRGB color space encoded with the sRGB gamma (average gamma of 2.2).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": _lift, gamma, gain (ProPhoto RGB)_ is the same as the previous mode but works in ProPhoto RGB space, encoded linearly. In this mode, the RGB parameters are corrected in XYZ luminance (Y channel) internally so they affect only the color, and only the “factors” adjust the luminance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": _slope, offset, power (ProPhoto RGB)_ applies the ASC CDL in ProPhoto RGB space, encoded linearly. As with the previous mode, the RGB parameters are corrected in XYZ luminance internally. In this mode, the slope parameter acts as an exposure compensation, the offset acts as a black level correction, and the power acts as a gamma correction. All parameters will have some impact on the whole luminance range but the slope will mostly affect the highlights, the offset will mostly affect the shadows, and the power will mostly affect the mid-tones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color control sliders\n"
": This combobox selection affects the user interface used for the shadows, mid-tones and highlights controls. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": _RGBL_ controls allow direct access to the RGB parameters that will be sent to the algorithm and internally adjusted in XYZ luminance, depending on the mode used. They are the only ones stored in darktable's development history.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": _HSL_ controls are more intuitive, but are only an interface: the hues and saturations are computed dynamically from and to the RGB parameters and never stored. During the HSL to RGB conversion, the HSL lightness is always assumed to be 50%, so the RGB parameters are always balanced to avoid lightness changes. However, during the RGB to HSL conversion, the HSL lightness is not corrected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": As a consequence, editing in RGB, then in HSL, then again in RGB will not retain the original RGB parameters, but will normalize them so their HSL lightness is 50%. The difference is barely noticeable in most cases, especially using the modes that already correct the RGB parameters internally in XYZ luminance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": In both modes, additional “factor” sliders act on all RGB channels at once. Their effect is similar to the controls of the [_levels_](./levels.md) module and affect only the luminance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input saturation\n"
": A saturation correction applied before the color balance. This can be used to dampen colors before adjusting the balance, to make difficult images easier to process. When you entirely desaturate the image, this creates a luminance-based monochrome image that can be used as a luminance mask, to create color filters with the _color balance_ settings, like a split-toning or sepia effect (when used with blending modes).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"output saturation\n"
": A saturation correction applied after the color balance. This is useful once you have found a proper hue balance but find the effect too heavy, so you can adjust the global saturation at once instead of editing each channel saturation separately at the expense of possibly messing up the colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast / contrast fulcrum\n"
": The contrast slider allows the luminance separation to be increased. The fulcrum value defines the luminance value that will not be affected by the contrast correction, so the contrast will roll over the fulcrum. Luminance values above the fulcrum will be amplified almost linearly. Luminance values below the fulcrum value will be compressed with a power function (creating a toe). This correction comes after the output saturation and is applied on all RGB channels separately, so hues and saturations might not be preserved in case of dramatic settings (shadows might be resaturated, highlights might be desaturated, and some color shift is to be expected).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shadows, mid-tones, highlights\n"
": Depending on the mode used, the shadows settings will control either the lift or the offset, the mid-tones settings will control either the gamma or the power, and the highlights settings will control either the gain or the slope. Parameters are transferred unaltered when you change the mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": In _RGBL_ mode, the RGB sliders' range is limited to \\[-0.5; 0.5\\]. In _HSL_ mode, the saturation sliders range is limited to \\[0%; 25%\\]. Values outside of these bounds can be defined with keyboard input by right-clicking on the slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The shadows, mid-tones and highlights sliders can take up a great deal of space in the _color balance_ module. The overall layout of these sliders can therefore be cycled through three different layouts by clicking on the _shadows, mid-tones, highlights_ heading. You can also set the default layout with [preferences > darkroom > colorbalance slider block layout](../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"optimize luma\n"
": The color-picker beside the optimize luma label will select the whole image and optimize the factors for shadows, mid-tones and highlights so that the average luminance of the image is 50% Lab, the maximum is 100% and the minimum is 0%, at the output of this module. This is essentially histogram normalization, similar to that performed by the [_levels_](./levels.md) module. The optimizer is only really accurate when used in _slope, offset, power_ mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": If you want more control, you can define three control patches by using the color pickers beside each factor slider to sample luminance in selected areas. The _shadows_ color picker samples the minimum luminance, the _mid-tones_ color picker samples the average luminance, and the _highlights_ color picker samples the maximum luminance. The most sensitive parameter is the mid-tones factor, since selecting a slightly different area can lead to dramatic parameter changes. Using the factors color pickers alone, without triggering the luma optimization, will allow you to perform adjustments without general optimization, but each parameter is always computed taking the other two into account. Once patches are selected, the label changes to read “optimize luma from patches”. To reset one patch, you can just redo the selection. Patches are not saved in the parameters and are retained only during the current session.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": It is important to note that the luminance adjustment targets only the output of the _color balance_ module and does not account for adjustments performed in other modules later in the pixelpipe (e.g. [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md), [_tone curve_](./tone-curve.md), [_color zones_](./color-zones.md), [_levels_](./levels.md)). Using the _color balance_ module to remap the luminance globally on the image is not recommended because it does not preserve the original colors -- modules such as [_tone curve_](./tone-curve.md) or [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md) are better suited for this purpose. Luminance adjustments in _color balance_ are better performed, in combination with color adjustments, using masks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"neutralize colors\n"
": In an image where some areas are exposed to direct sunlight and some areas are exposed to reflected light (shadows), or where several artificial light sources are present simultaneously, shadows and highlights often have different color temperatures. These images are particularly difficult to correct since no general white balance will match all the colors at once. The color neutralization optimizer aims at helping you find the complementary color for shadows, mid-tones, and highlights so that all the color casts are reverted, and the average color of the image is a neutral gray.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": As with the luma optimization, the color picker beside the neutralize colors label will trigger a general optimization over the whole image. This works fairly well in landscape photography, or for any photograph with a full spectrum of colors and luminances. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": For night and events photography, this will most likely fail and you will need to manually input the sampling areas with the color-pickers beside each hue slider. For the highlights sample, use a color exposed to spotlights that should be neutral white or light gray. For the shadows sample, use a color exposed to ambient light that should be neutral black or dark gray. For the mid-tones sample, use a color exposed by both ambient and spotlights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": The success of the optimization depends on the quality of the samples. Not every set of samples will converge to a good solution and you need to ensure that the color patches you choose are really a neutral color in real life. In many cases the optimizer will output the correct hue but an excessive saturation that will need some extra tweaking. In some cases, no valid optimization will be delivered and you will need to reset the saturation parameters and start over, or simply stop after the patches selection. Note that in the auto-optimization, the maximum saturation is 25%, which might not be enough in very few cases but will avoid inconsistent results in most.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": If you select color patches from the hue color pickers without triggering the optimization, the software will only perform one round of optimization and then stop. This allows you to control each luminance range separately and avoid divergence of the solution in corner cases. The hue and saturation corrections are computed taking into account the two other luminance ranges and three factors, and will always output the complementary color of the selected area. If you want to reinforce the color of the area instead, you can then add 180° to the computed hue. Once patches are selected, the label changes to read “neutralize colors from patches”. To reset one patch you can just redo the selection. Patches are not saved in the parameters and are retained only during the current session. The parameters found by the automatic neutralization are accurate only in _slope, offset, power_ mode, but can work to some extent in _lift, gamma, gain_ mode too.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color calibration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A fully-featured color-space correction, white balance adjustment and channel mixer module. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This simple yet powerful module can be used in the following ways:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To adjust the white balance ([chromatic adaptation](#white-balance-in-the-chromatic-adaptation-transformation-cat-tab)), working in tandem with the [_white balance_](./white-balance.md) module. Here, the _white balance_ module makes some initial adjustments (required for the [_demosaic_](./demosaic.md) module to work effectively), and the _color calibration_ module then calculates a more perceptually-accurate white balance after the input color profile has been applied.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As a simple RGB [channel mixer](#channel-mixing), adjusting the R, G and B output channels based on the R, G and B input channels, to perform cross-talk color-grading.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To adjust the [color saturation and brightness](#brightness-and-colorfulness-tabs) of the image, based on the relative strength of the R, G and B channels of each pixel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To produce a [grayscale output](#gray-tab) based on the relative strengths of the R, G and B channels, in a way similar to the response of black and white film to a light spectrum.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To improve the color accuracy of the input color profile using a [color checker](#extracting-settings-using-a-color-checker) chart.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "White Balance in the Chromatic Adaptation Transformation (CAT) tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Chromatic adaptation aims to predict how all surfaces in the scene would look if they had been lit by another illuminant. What we actually want to predict, though, is how those surfaces would have looked if they had been lit by the same illuminant as your monitor, in order to make all colors in the scene match the change of illuminant. White balance, on the other hand, aims only at ensuring that whites and grays are really neutral (R = G = B) and doesn’t really care about the rest of the color range. White balance is therefore only a partial chromatic adaptation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Chromatic adaptation is controlled within the Chromatic Adaptation Transformation (CAT) tab of the _color calibration_ module. When used in this way the _white balance_ module is still required as it needs to perform a basic white balance operation (connected to the input color profile values). This technical white balancing (\"camera reference\" mode) is a flat setting that makes grays lit by a standard D65 illuminant look achromatic, and makes the demosaicing process more accurate, but does not perform any perceptual adaptation according to the scene. The actual chromatic adaptation is then performed by the _color calibration_ module, on top of those corrections performed by the _white balance_ and _input color profile_ modules. The use of custom matrices in the _input color profile_ module is therefore discouraged. Additionally, the RGB coefficients in the _white balance_ module need to be accurate in order for this module to work in a predictable way.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _color calibration_ and _white balance_ modules can be automatically applied to perform chromatic adaptation for new edits by setting the chromatic adaptation workflow option ([preferences > processing > auto-apply chromatic adaptation defaults](../../preferences-settings/processing.md)) to \"modern\". If you prefer to perform all white balancing within the _white balance_ module, a \"legacy\" option is also provided. Neither option precludes the use of other modules (such as [_color balance RGB_](./color-balance-rgb.md)) for creative color grading further along the pixel pipeline.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, _color calibration_ performs chromatic adaptation by:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "reading the RAW file's Exif data to fetch the scene white balance set by the camera,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "adjusting this setting using the camera reference white balance from the _white balance_ module,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "further adjusting this setting with the input color profile in use (standard matrix only).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For consistency, the _color calibration_ module's default settings always assume that the standard matrix is used in the _input color profile_ module -- any non-standard settings in this module are ignored. However, _color calibration_'s defaults can read any auto-applied preset in the _white balance_ module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is also worth noting that, unlike the _white balance_ module, _color calibration_ can be used with [masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md). This means that you can selectively correct different parts of the image to account for differing light sources.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To achieve this, create an instance of the _color calibration_ module to perform global adjustments using a mask to exclude those parts of the image that you wish to handle differently. Then create a second instance of the module reusing the mask from the first instance (inverted) using a [raster mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/raster.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "CAT tab workflow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The default illuminant and color space used by the chromatic adaptation are initialised from the Exif metadata of the RAW file. There are four options available in the CAT tab to set these parameters manually:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use the color-picker (to the right of the color patch) to select a neutral color from the image or, if one is unavailable, select the entire image. In this case, the algorithm finds the average color within the chosen area and sets that color as the illuminant. This method relies on the \"gray-world\" assumption, which predicts that the average color of a natural scene will be neutral. This method will not work for artificial scenes, for example those with painted surfaces.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Select \"_(AI) detect from edges_\", which uses a machine-learning technique to detect the illuminant using the entire image. This algorithm finds the average gradient color over the edges in the image and sets that color as the illuminant. This method relies on the \"gray-edge\" assumption, which may fail if large chromatic aberrations are present. As with any edge-detection method, it is sensitive to noise and poorly suited to high-ISO images, but it is very well suited for artificial scenes where no neutral colors are available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Select \"_(AI) detect from surfaces_\", which combines the two previous methods, also using the entire image. This algorithm finds the average color within the image, giving greater weight to areas where sharp details are found and colors are strongly correlated. This makes it more immune to noise than the _edge_ variant and more immune to legitimate non-neutral surfaces than the naïve average, but sharp colored textures (like green grass) are likely to make it fail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Select \"_as shot in camera_\" to restore the camera defaults and re-read the RAW Exif.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The color patch shows the color of the currently calculated illuminant projected into sRGB space. The aim of the chromatic adaptation algorithm is to turn this color into pure white, which does not necessarily means shifting the image toward its *perceptual* opponent color. If the illuminant is properly set, the image will be given the same tint as shown in the color patch when the module is disabled.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To the left of the color patch is the _CCT_ (correlated color temperature) approximation. This is the closest temperature, in kelvin, to the illuminant currently in use. In most image processing software it is customary to set the white balance using a combination of temperature and tint. However, when the illuminant is far from daylight, the CCT becomes inaccurate and irrelevant, and the CIE (International Commission on Illumination) discourages its use in such conditions. The CCT reading informs you of the closest CCT match found:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the CCT is followed by \"_(daylight)_\", this means that the current illuminant is close to an ideal daylight spectrum ± 0.5 %, and the CCT figure is therefore meaningful. In this case, you are advised to use the \"_D (daylight)_\" illuminant.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the CCT is followed by \"_(black  body)_\", this means that the current illuminant is close to an ideal black body (Planckian) spectrum ± 0.5 %, and the CCT figure is therfore meaningful. In this case, you are advised to use the \"_Planckian (black body)_\" illuminant.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the CCT is followed by \"_(invalid)_\", this means that the CCT figure is meaningless and wrong, because we are too far from either a daylight or a black body light spectrum. In this case, you are advised to use the _custom_ illuminant. The chromatic adaptation will still perform as expected (see the note below), so the \"_(invalid)_\" tag only means that the current illuminant color is not accurately tied to the displayed CCT. This tag is nothing to be concerned about -- it is merely there to tell you to stay away from the daylight and planckian illuminants because they will not behave as you might expect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When one of the above illuminant detection methods is used, the module checks where the calculated illuminant sits using the two idealized spectra (daylight and black body) and chooses the most accurate spectrum model to use in its _illuminant_ parameter. The user-interface will change accordingly:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A temperature slider will be provided if the detected illuminant is close to a _D (daylight)_ or _Planckian (black body)_ spectrum, for which the CCT is meaningful.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hue and chroma sliders in CIE 1976 Luv space are offered for the _custom_ illuminant, which allows direct selection of the illuminant color in a perceptual framework without any intermediate assumption.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Internally, the illuminant is represented by its absolute chromaticity coordinates in CIE xyY color space. The illuminant selection options in the module are merely interfaces to set up this chromaticity from real-world relationships and are intended to make this process faster. It does not matter to the algorithm if the CCT is tagged \"invalid\" -- this just means that the relationship between the CCT and the corresponding xyY coordinates is not physically accurate. Regardless, the color set for the illuminant, as displayed in the patch, will always be honored by the algorithm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When switching from one illuminant to another, the module attempts to translate the previous settings to the new illumninant as accurately as possible. Switching from any illuminant to _custom_ preserves your settings entirely, since the _custom_ illuminant is a general case. Switching between other modes, or from _custom_ to any other mode, will not precisely preserve your settings from the previous mode due to rounding errors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Other hard-coded _illuminants_ are available (see below). Their values come from standard CIE illuminants and are absolute. You can use them directly if you know exactly what kind of light bulb was used to illuminate the scene and if you trust your camera's input profile and reference (D65) coefficients to be accurate. Otherwise, see [_caveats_](#caveats) below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "CAT tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"adaptation\n"
": The working color space in which the module will perform its chromatic adaptation transform and channel mixing. The following options are provided:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _Linear Bradford (1985)_: This is accurate for illuminants close to daylight and is compatible with the ICC v4 standard, but produces out-of-gamut colors for more difficult illuminants.\n"
": - _CAT16 (2016)_: This is the default option and is more robust in avoiding imaginary colors while working with large gamut or saturated cyan and purple. It is more accurate than the Bradford CAT in most cases.\n"
": - _Non-linear Bradford (1985)_: This can sometimes produce better results than the linear version but is unreliable.\n"
": - _XYZ_: This is the least accurate method and is generally not recommended except for testing and debugging purposes.\n"
": - _none (disable)_: Disable any adaptation and use the pipeline working RGB space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"illuminant\n"
": The type of illuminant assumed to have lit the scene. Choose from the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _same as pipeline (D50)_: Do not perform chromatic adaptation in this module instance but just perform channel mixing, using the selected _adaptation_ color space.\n"
": - _CIE standard illuminant_: Choose from one of the CIE standard illuminants (daylight, incandescent, fluorescent, equi-energy, or black body), or a non-standard \"LED light\" illuminant. These values are all pre-computed -- as long as your camera sensor is properly profiled, you can just use them as-is. For illuminants that lie near the Planckian locus, an additional \"temperature\" control is also provided (see below).\n"
": - _custom_: If a neutral gray patch is available in the image, the color of the illuminant can be selected using the color picker, or can be manually specified using hue and saturation sliders (in LCh perceptual color space). The color swatch next to the color picker shows the color of the calculated illuminant used in the CAT compensation. The color picker can also be used to restrict the area used for AI detection (below).\n"
": - _(AI) detect from image surfaces_: This algorithm obtains the average color of image patches that have a high covariance between chroma channels in YUV space and a high intra-channel variance. In other words, it looks for parts of the image that appear as though they should be gray, and discards flat colored surfaces that may be legitimately non-gray. It also discards chroma noise as well as chromatic aberrations.\n"
": - _(AI) detect from image edges_: Unlike the _white balance_ module's auto-white-balancing which relies on the \"gray world\" assumption, this method auto-detects a suitable illuminant using the \"gray edge\" assumption, by calculating the Minkowski p-norm (p = 8) of the laplacian and trying to minimize it. That is to say, it assumes that edges should have the same gradient over all channels (gray edges). It is more sensitive to noise than the previous surface-based detection method.\n"
": - _as shot in camera_: Calculate the illuminant based on the white balance settings provided by the camera.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"temperature\n"
": Adjust the color temperature of the illuminant. Move the slider to the right to assume a more blue illuminant, which will make the white-balanced image appear warmer/more red. Move the slider to the left to assume a more red illuminant, which makes the image appear cooler/more blue after compensation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": This control is only provided for illuminants that lie near the Planckian locus and provides fine-adjustment along that locus. For other illuminants the concept of \"color temperature\" doesn't make sense, so no temperature slider is provided.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": For custom white balance, set the _hue_ of the illuminant color in LCh color space (derived from CIE Luv space).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"chroma\n"
": For custom white balance, set the _chroma_ (or saturation) of the illuminant color in LCh color space (derived from CIE Luv space).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"gamut compression\n"
":  Most camera sensors are slightly sensitive to invisible UV wavelengths, which are recorded on the blue channel and produce \"imaginary\" colors. Once corrected by the input color profile, these colors will end up out of gamut (that is, it may no longer be possible to represent certain colors as a valid [R,G,B] triplet with positive values in the working color space) and produce visual artifacts in gradients. The chromatic adaptation may also push other valid colors out of gamut, at the same time pushing any already out-of-gamut colors even further out of gamut. \n"
": _Gamut compression_ uses a perceptual, non-destructive, method to attempt to compress the chroma while preserving the luminance as-is and the hue as close as possible, in order to fit the whole image into the gamut of the pipeline working color space. One example where this feature is very useful is for scenes containing blue LED lights, which are often quite problematic and can result in ugly gamut clipping in the final image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clip negative RGB from gamut\n"
": Remove any negative RGB values (set them to zero). This helps to deal with bad black level as well as the blue channel clipping issues that may occur with blue LED lights. This option is destructive for color (it may change the hue) but ensures a valid RGB output no matter what. It should never be disabled unless you want to take care of the gamut mapping manually and understand what you are doing. In that case, use the _black level correction_ in the _exposure_ module to get rid of any negative RGB (RGB means light, which is energy, and which should always be a positive quantity), then increase the _gamut compression_ until no solid black patches remain in the image. Proper denoising may help getting rid of odd RGB values too. Note that this approach may still be insufficient to recover some deep and luminous shades of blue. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note 1**: It has been reported that some OpenCL drivers don't play well when negative RGB are present in the pixel pipeline, because many pixel operators use logarithms and power functions (_filmic_, _color balance_, all the CIE Lab <-> CIE XYZ color space conversions), which are not defined for negative numbers. Although the inputs are sanitized before sensitive operations, it is not enough for some OpenCL drivers, which will output isolated `NaN` (Not a Number) values. These `NaN` values may be subsequently spread by local filters (blurring and sharpening operations, like _sharpness_, _local contrast_, _contrast equalizer_, _low pass_, _high pass_, _surface blur_, and _filmic_ highlights reconstruction), resulting in large black, grey or white squares.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In all these cases, you **must** enable the \"clip negative RGB from gamut\" option in the _color calibration_ module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note 2**: A common case for failure of the color algorithms in _color calibration_ (especially the gamut compression) is pixels that have a luminance value of 0 (Y channel of the CIE 1931 XYZ space), but non-zero chromaticity values (X and Z channels of the CIE 1931 XYZ space). This case is a numerical oddity that matches no physical reality (a pixel with no luminance should have no chromaticity either), will produce a division by zero in xyY and Yuv color spaces, and will create `NaN` RGB values as a result. This issue is **not** corrected inside _color calibration_ because it is a symptom of a bad input profiling and/or a bad black point level, and needs to be addressed manually either by adjusting the input color profile with the channel mixer or in the _exposure_ module's _black level correction_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "CAT warnings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The chromatic adaptation in this module relies on a number of assumptions about the earlier processing steps in the pipeline in order to work correctly, and it can be easy to inadvertently break those assumptions in subtle ways. To help you to avoid these kinds of mistakes, the _color calibration_ module will show warnings in the following circumstances.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the _color calibration_ module is set up to perform chromatic adaptation but the _white balance_ module is not set to \"camera reference\", warnings will be shown in both modules. These errors can be resolved either by setting the _white balance_ module to \"camera reference\" or by disabling chromatic adaptation in the _color calibration_ module. Note that some sensors may require minor corrections within the _white balance_ module in which case these warnings can be ignored.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If two or more instances of _color calibration_ have been created, each attempting to perform chromatic adaptation, an error will be shown on the second instance. This could be a valid use case (for instance where masks have been set up to apply different white balances to different non-overlapping areas of the image) in which case the warnings can be ignored. For most other cases, chromatic adaptation should be disabled in one of the instances to avoid double-corrections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "  By default, if an instance of the _color calibration_ module is already performing chromatic adaptation, each new instance you create will automatically have its adaptation set to \"none (bypass)\" to avoid this \"double-correction\" error.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The chromatic adaptation modes in _color calibration_ can be disabled by either setting the _adaptation_ to \"none (bypass)\" or setting the _illuminant_ to \"same as pipeline (D50)\" in the CAT tab.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "These warnings are intended to prevent common and easy mistakes while using the automatic default presets in the module in a typical RAW editing workflow. When using custom presets and some specific workflows, such as editing film scans or JPEGs, these warnings can and should be ignored. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Advanced users can disable module warnings in [preferences > processing > show warning messages](../../preferences-settings/processing.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "channel mixing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The remainder of this module is a standard channel mixer, allowing you to adjust the output R, G, B, colorfulness, brightness and gray of the module based on the relative strengths of the R, G and B input channels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Channel mixing is performed in the color space defined by the _adaptation_ control on the [CAT tab](#cat-tab-controls). For all practical purposes, these CAT spaces are particular RGB spaces tied to human physiology and proportional to the light emissions in the scene, but they still behave in the same way as any other RGB space. The use of any of the CAT spaces can make the channel mixer tuning process easier, due to their connection with human physiology, but it is also possible to mix channels in the RGB working space of the pipeline by setting the _adaptation_ to \"none (bypass)\". To perform channel mixing in one of the _adaptation_ color spaces without chromatic adaptation, set the _illuminant_ to \"same as pipeline (D50)\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: The actual colors of the CAT or RGB primaries used for the channel mixing, projected to sRGB display space, are painted in the background of the RGB sliders, so you can get a sense of the color shift that will result from your altered settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Channel mixing is a process that defines a boosting/muting factor for each channel as a ratio of all the original channels. Instead of entering a single flat correction that ties the output value of a channel to its input value (for example, `R_output = R_input × correction`), the correction to each channel is dependent on the input of _all_ of the channels for each pixel (for example, `R_output = R_input × R_correction + G_input × G_correction + B_input × B_correction`). Thus a pixel's channels contribute to each other (a process known as \"cross-talk\") which is equivalent to rotating the primary colors of the color space in 3D. This is, in effect, digital simulation of physical color filters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Although rotating primary colors in 3D is ultimately equivalent to applying a general hue rotation, the connection between the RGB corrections and the resulting perceptual hue rotation is not directly predictable, which makes the process non-intuitive. \"R\", \"G\" and \"B\" should be taken as a mixture of 3 lights that we dial up and down, not as a set of colors or hues. Also, since RGB tristimulus does not decouple luminance and chrominance, but is an additive lighting setup, the \"G\" channel is more strongly tied to human luminance perception than the \"R\" and \"B\" ones. All pixels have a non-zero G channel, which implies that any correction to the G channel is likely to affect all pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The channel mixing process is therefore tied to a physical interpretation of the RGB tristimulus (as additive lights), which makes it well-suited for primary color grading and illuminant corrections, and blends the color changes smoothly. However, trying to understand and predict it from a perceptual point of view (luminance, hue and saturation) is going to fail and is discouraged.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: The \"R\", \"G\" and \"B\" labels on the channels of the color spaces in this module are merely conventions formed out of habit. These channels do not necessarily look \"red\", \"green\" and \"blue\", and users are advised against trying to make sense out of them based on their names. This is a general principle that applies to _any_ RGB space used in any application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "R, G and B tabs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "At its most basic level, you can think of the R, G and B tabs of the _color calibration_ module as a type of matrix multiplication between a 3x3 matrix and the input [R G B] values. This is in fact very similar to what a matrix-based ICC color profile does, except that the user can input the matrix coefficients via the darktable GUI rather than reading the coefficients from an ICC profile file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ Rr Rg Rb ┐     ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ Gr Gg Gb │  X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ Br Bg Bb ┘     └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If, for example, you've been provided with a matrix to transform from one color space to another, you can enter the matrix coefficients into the _channel mixer_ as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "select the _R_ tab and then set the Rr, Rg & Rb values using the R, G and B input sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "select the _G_ tab and then set the Gr, Gg & Gb values using the R, G and B input sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "select the _B_ tab and then set the Br, Bg & Bb values using the R, G and B input sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, the mixing function in _color calibration_ just copies the input [R G B] channels straight over to the matching output channels. This is equivalent to multiplying by the identity matrix:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ 1  0  0 ┐      ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ 0  1  0 │   X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ 0  0  1 ┘      └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For a more intuitive understanding of how the mixing sliders on the R, G and B tabs behave, consider the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the _R_ destination channel, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more \"red\". Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more \"cyan\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the _G_ destination channel, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more \"green\". Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more \"magenta\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the _B_ destination channel, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more \"blue\". Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more \"yellow\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "R, G and B tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following controls are shown for each of the R, G and B tabs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input R/G/B\n"
": Choose how much the input R, G and B channels influence the output channel relating to the tab concerned.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to normalize the coefficients to try to preserve the overall brightness of this channel in the final image as compared to the input image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "brightness and colorfulness tabs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The brightness and colorfulness (color saturation) of pixels in an image can also be adjusted based on the R, G and B input channels. This uses the same basic algorithm that the [_filmic rgb_](filmic-rgb.md) module uses for tone mapping (which preserves RGB ratios) and for mid-tones saturation (which massages them).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation algorithm\n"
": This control allows you to upgrade the saturation algorithm to the new 2021 version, for edits produced prior to darktable 3.6 -- it will not appear for edits that already use the latest version.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "colorfulness tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input R/G/B\n"
": Adjust the color saturation of pixels, based on the R, G and B channels of those pixels. For example, adjusting the _input R_ slider will affect the color saturation of pixels containing a lot of \"R\" more than pixels containing only a small amount of \"R\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to try to keep the overall saturation constant between the input and output images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "brightness tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input R/G/B\n"
": Adjust the brightness of certain colors in the image, based on the R, G and B channels of those colors. For example, adjusting the _input R_ slider will affect the brightness of colors containing a lot of R channel much more than colors containing only a small amount of R channel. When darkening/brightening a pixel, the ratio of the R, G and B channels for that pixel is maintained, in order to preserve the hue.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to try to keep the overall brightness constant between the input and output images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "gray tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Another very useful application of _color calibration_ is the ability to mix the channels together to produce a grayscale output -- a monochrome image. Select the _gray_ tab, and set the R, G and B sliders to control how much each channel contributes to the brightness of the output. This is equivalent to the following matrix multiplication:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GRAY_out  =   [ r  g  b ]  X  ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"                              │ G_in │\n"
"                              └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When dealing with skin tones, the relative weights of the three channels will affect the level of detail in the image. Placing more weight on R (e.g. [0.9, 0.3, -0.3]) will make for smooth skin tones, whereas emphasising G (e.g. [0.4, 0.75, -0.15]) will bring out more detail. In both cases the B channel is reduced to avoid emphasising unwanted skin texture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "gray tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input R/G/B\n"
": Choose how much each of the R, G and B channels contribute to the gray level of the output. The image will only be converted to monochrome if the three sliders add up to some non-zero value. Adding more B will tend to bring out more details, adding more R will tend to smooth skin tones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to try to keep the overall brightness constant as the sliders are adjusted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "extracting settings using a color checker"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Since the channel mixer is essentially an RGB matrix (similar to the [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) used for RAW images) it can be used to improve the color accuracy of the input color profile by computing ad-hoc color calibration settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "These computed settings aim to minimize the color difference between the scene reference and the camera recording in a given lighting situation. This is equivalent to creating a generic ICC color profile but here, the profile is instead stored as module settings that can be saved as presets or styles, to be shared and re-used between images. Such profiles are meant to complement and refine the generic input profile but do not replace it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This feature can assist with:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "handling difficult illuminants, such as low [CRI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_rendering_index) light bulbs, for which a mere white balancing will never suffice,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "digitizing artworks or commercial products where an accurate rendition of the original colors is required,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "neutralizing a number of different cameras to the same ground-truth, in multi-camera photo sessions, in order to obtain a consistent base look and share the color editing settings with a consistent final look,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "obtaining a sane color pipeline from the start, nailing white balance and removing any bounced-light color cast at once, with minimal effort and time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "supported color checker targets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Users are not currently permitted to use custom targets, but a limited number of verified color checkers (from reputable manufacturers) are supported:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "X-Rite / Gretag MacBeth Color Checker 24 (pre- and post-2014),\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Datacolor SpyderCheckr 24,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Datacolor SpyderCheckr 48.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Users are discouraged from obtaining cheap, off-brand, color targets as color constancy between batches cannot possibly be asserted at such prices. Inaccurate color checkers will only defeat the purpose of color calibration and possibly make things worse.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "IT7 and IT8 charts are not supported since they are hardly portable and not practical for use on-location for ad-hoc profiles. These charts are better suited for creating generic color profiles, undertaken using a standard illuminant, for example with [Argyll CMS](https://encrypted.pcode.nl/blog/index.html%3Fp=594.html).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: X-Rite changed the formula of their pigments in 2014, which slightly altered the color of the patches. Both formulas are supported in darktable, but you should be careful to choose the correct reference for your target. If in doubt, try both and choose the one that yields the lowest average delta E after calibration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "prerequisites"
msgstr "prerequisiti"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In order to use this feature you will need to take a test shot of a supported color checker chart, on-location, under appropriate lighting conditions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "frame the chart in the center 50% of the camera's field, to ensure that the image is free of vignetting,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "ensure that the main light source is far enough from the chart to give an even lighting field over the surface of the chart,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "adjust the angle between the light, chart and lens to prevent reflections and gloss on the color patches,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "for the best quality profile you should capture an image with the appropriate brightness. To achieve this, take a few bracketed images (between -1 and +1 EV) of your color checker and load them into darktable, ensuring that all modules between _color calibration_ and _output color profile_ are disabled. Choose the image where the white patch has a brightness L of 94-96% in CIE Lab space or a luminance Y of 83-88% in CIE XYZ space (use the global color picker). This step is not strictly necessary -- alternatively you can take a single image and apply the exposure compensation as recommended in the profile report.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the lighting conditions are close to a standard D50 to D65 illuminant (direct natural light, no colored bounced light), the color checker shot can be used to produce a generic profile that will be suitable for any daylight illuminant with only a slight adjustment of the white balance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the lighting conditions are peculiar and far from standard illuminants, the color checker shot will be only usable as an ad-hoc profile for pictures taken in the same lighting conditions.\n"
msgstr ""

