#: content/overview/workflow/export.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click the \"export\" button to save your processed images in the selected location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/export.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** While JPEG is useful for most purposes, if you wish to perform further edits in a raster editor like GIMP or Krita, it is normally better to export in tiff format._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#: content/special-topics/darktable-chart/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "process"
msgstr "processo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This section is intended to get you comfortable processing images in the darkroom view using a _scene-referred_ workflow. You are advised to follow the guidelines provided below, up to the end of the [_image processing in 3 modules_](#image-processing-in-3-modules) section and then choose other areas to learn as-and-when you need to use those techniques in your images. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "editing shapes"
msgid "getting started"
msgstr "modificare le forme"

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "take a well-exposed photograph"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Good image processing techniques start in the camera -- a well-exposed image (without blown highlights or heavily crushed blacks) will always make post-processing much more straightforward. Under- or over-exposure can be \"fixed\" by darktable to some extent but no software can recover information that is not present in the Raw image. Where possible, you are advised to use [exposure to-the-right (ETTR)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exposing_to_the_right) techniques to maximize the amount of data available for processing. As a general rule of thumb, it is safe to under-expose all images by 0.5 to 1 EV (by reducing the ISO sensitivity if possible) even if the in-camera preview looks darker than expected (the preview is not the raw data).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "scene-referred workflow: a new approach"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you have used other Raw software in the past (or darktable prior to version 3.0) you may notice some significant differences from what you are used to -- darktable now uses a _scene-referred_ approach for most of its processing modules. This approach is used extensively in cinematography and is known to be much more robust than the traditional _display-referred_ approach.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In _display-referred processing_ the data from your Raw file is initially compressed into a range that represents pure black as 0 and pure white as 1, fixing mid-gray at 0.5. A tone curve is automatically (and irreversably) applied to this data to make the image look \"good\" on your display and subsequent edits are carried out on top of this already highly-modified image data. The cost of _display-referred_ is an early loss of the relationship between pixel luminosity and saturation (usually also involving hue shifts), which is responsible for the infamous \"HDR look\" when the dynamic range increases.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the real world, \"pure black\" does not really exist (there is always _some_ light) and there is no limit to how bright things can be (so no \"pure white\" either). _Scene-referred processing_ attempts to retain the physical properties of the scene for as long as possible by placing the Raw data on an unbounded linear scale and only compressing the data to the dynamic range of your display after image processing is complete.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In a scene-referred workflow many common tools (tone curves and levels, for example) are no longer useful ways to manipulate the image, since they rely on now-invalid definitions of black, white and gray. Experienced users may need to learn new techniques and discard old ones, but will be rewarded with much more robust and predictable outputs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Set [preferences > processing > auto-apply pixel workflow defaults](../../preferences-settings/processing.md) to \"scene-referred\" now. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_Enter preferences by clicking on the gear icon in the [top panel](../user-interface/top-panel.md)_. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "white balance and color calibration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Most processing software uses a traditional temperature/tint model for adjusting the white balance of an image. In darktable, the [color calibration module](../../module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md) provides a much more robust and flexible approach, allowing you to explicitly define the color of the light source. This is particularly useful for scenes illuminated by artificial lighting.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Please note that the [white balance](../../module-reference/processing-modules/white-balance.md) module is still enabled in this approach, but its settings normally should not be altered.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Set [preferences > processing > auto-apply chromatic adaptation defaults](../../preferences-settings/processing.md) to \"modern\" now.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "edit in a controlled environment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Image processing should be performed in a controlled environment, lit by a white light source against a background approximating mid-gray, and on a monitor that has been properly calibrated.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "While this may not be practical in many home editing environments you _can_ control the background colors on your monitor's display. You should set the darktable color scheme to use one of the \"grey\" themes and use the [color assessment mode](../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md) when altering tones and colors in your image. Dark themes might look good but, unless you are processing images to be viewed on a cinema screen in a darkened room, they should not be used for photo processing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Set [preferences > general > theme](../../preferences-settings/general.md) to \"darktable-elegant-grey\" or \"darktable-icons-grey\" now.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "enter the darkroom"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Choose an image to edit from the lighttable view and double-click to load that image into the darkroom view. For now try to choose an image that is well exposed -- we will discuss some techniques to recover badly-exposed images later.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the darkroom view, you will see a list of [processing modules](../../darkroom/processing-modules/_index.md) to the right of your image. Each module performs its own processing on the image, in the order shown in the module list, starting at the bottom of the list and moving up to the top. You can think of this like a stack of building blocks where each block builds on the processing performed by the modules below it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "On the left hand side is the [history stack](../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md) (you may need to expand the module), which shows the order in which adjustments were made to the controls of the various modules. This allows you to undo changes by reverting to an earlier step in the history stack. You will see that a number of modules are applied automatically -- these are needed in order to generate a legible image from the Raw data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is important to understand the distinction between the order of the modules on the right-hand-side of the screen (which represents the order in which modules are _executed_) and the order of the modules in the history stack (which represents the order in which modules were _modified_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "The [filmstrip](../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/filmstrip.md) below the image allows you to select more images.\n"
msgid "To the top right is the [scopes](../../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/scopes.md) module, which shows the spread of tones/colors in your image.\n"
msgstr "Il [filmstrip](../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/filmstrip.md) sotto l'immagine ti permette di selezionarne altre.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you have previously viewed or edited the image in the darkroom view, start by _discarding history_ (click the _reset_ button in the [_history stack_](../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md)). This will reapply defaults using your new settings and provide a clean starting point for editing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "why doesn't the raw image look like the JPEG?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_...because you haven't processed it yet_\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "One of the first things people notice when switching from lighttable to darkroom view is that the image looks different -- often flatter and less saturated than that shown in the lighttable view. This is because the darkroom view displays the (mostly unprocessed) Raw image, but the lighttable view initially displays the (in-camera) JPEG preview. Now that you have opened the image in the darkroom view, the lighttable view will update to show the edited version.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Most Raw software goes to great lengths to reproduce the look of standard camera JPEGs out of the box. While this can be useful (if you only want to make very minor adjustments to the camera's rendition of an image) we assume that you are using a Raw editor to make the image your own, and that the camera does not know how to do this. Certainly, if you are using the ETTR techniques mentioned above, the camera JPEG will rarely be close to how you want the final image to look. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The default settings in darktable are therefore intended to provide you with a neutral _starting point_ for further editing and nothing more. _We do not intend to change this_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Below the scopes module, at the top right of the screen, is a set of tabs into which darktable's modules are [grouped](../../darkroom/organization/module-groups.md). If you cannot find a module in one of the tabs you can use the search feature to locate it. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For the purposes of this guide, click on the hamburger icon (to the right of the tabs) and select the \"workflow: scene referred\" preset now.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "image processing in 3 modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following basic adjustments are fundamental to scene-referred editing and will be required, to some extent, on the majority of images. You can usually produce a good-looking image with these steps alone.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As you will be adjusting the tones and colors of the image, start by enabling [color assessment mode](../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md) (press Ctrl+B) and perform the following edits on the zoomed-out image while in this mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Set overall image brightness**: First, set the overall (average) brightness of the image (the mid-gray point) by adjusting the _exposure_ slider in the [_exposure_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md) module. This is a purely artistic setting and should be defined based on your intent -- for example, for a high-key image you will set the average brightness to be lighter than for a low-key image. The color assessment mode provides you with two reference points to assist with this by surrounding the image with a white frame against a middle-gray background. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "   At this point, don't worry if the brightest parts of your image lose detail -- this can be recovered in the next step.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "   _**Note:** The [lens correction](#correct-lens-distortions) module can also affect the image brightness so you may want to consider enabling it before adjusting exposure._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Set white and black points**: The next two steps use the [_filmic rgb_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md) module to define how the tones in your image will be mapped to the dynamic range of your display. Start by setting the _white_ and _black_ relative exposure sliders in the [_scene tab_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md#scene). These are purely technical settings, defining white and black relative to the mid-gray point you set in the previous step. If your image contains tones you want to treat as pure white or pure black you can use the color pickers beside the sliders to set these values (using the maximum and minimum brightness of the image). Otherwise set the values manually using the color assessment frames as a reference.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Adjust the contrast**: Now move to the [_look tab_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md#look) in _filmic rgb_ (for now we will skip the [_reconstruct tab_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb#reconstruct)). Enable the [_look only_ view](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md#graphic-display) at the top of the module to see a representation of the filmic tone curve, which consists of a straight section in the middle (used to set the contrast of the mid-tones) and curved sections at the top and bottom (where the shadows and highlights are compressed to fit the dynamic range of the display). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "   The _contrast_ slider changes the slope of the straight section (the mid-tone image contrast), the _latitude_ slider changes its length and the _shadows/highlights balance_ slider changes its position. There is a lot of give-and-take involved here -- if you want to increase the contrast of the mid-tones, you must sacrifice contrast in the shadows/highlights and vice versa. The default settings of this module are tuned to work for the majority of images but you should experiment with these sliders to understand how they affect the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "   _**Note:** The highlight compression in the filmic rgb module can cause detail to be lost in the highlights. You can mitigate this to some extent by reducing the _white relative exposure_, adjusting the _shadows/highlights balance_ or changing the _contrast in highlights_ setting in the [options tab](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md#options). The [tone equalizer](../../module-reference/processing-modules/tone-equalizer.md) module can also be used to reduce the relative brightness of the sky._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Color preservation**: The tone mapping in the filmic module attempts to redistribute the tones in your image without affecting color reproduction. While the default color preservation algorithm works for most images, you are encouraged to experiment by changing the _preserve chrominance_ setting in the [_options tab_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md#options) if you do not like how the colors appear. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Saturation**: Your image will probably not look very colorful at this point. You can adjust the global saturation of the image using the [color balance rgb](../../module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md) module. The \"basic colorfulness\" [preset](../../darkroom/processing-modules/presets.md) should provide you with generally-reasonable defaults, but you are encouraged to experiment further with these settings as required. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "   _**Note:** This guide assumes that the white balance of the image has been correctly captured by your camera. If this is not the case, you may need to make some corrections in the [color calibration](#color-calibration) module first._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can now switch off _color assessment mode_ by pressing Ctrl+B again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "other processing techniques"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "With practice the above workflow can quickly provide you with a reasonable-looking image, though most will need some additional work before they are ready for export. The following sections are intended to provide a brief outline of some more image processing techniques in darktable, with links to the relevant reference sections for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As a general rule, you should begin with the basic steps outlined in the previous section, then perform [_corrections_](#corrections) and finish with [_creative adjustments_](#creative-adjustments).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Traditional white balance correction attempts to ensure that whites and grays are really neutral (R = G = B) and doesn’t really try to manage the impact on other colors. The [_CAT tab of the color calibration module_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md#white-balance-in-the-chromatic-adaptation-transformation-cat-tab) extends this treatment to handle the remainder of the color range and works in a color space designed specifically for chromatic (color) adaptation. As with traditional white balance controls you can select a patch of neutral gray in your image to calculate the white balance, or use a selection of other automatic and manual methods. The default settings use the white balance from the image's Exif data and are usually sufficient.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you need to make adjustments in the _color calibration_ module, you may want to also revisit any saturation corrections you made earlier in the _color balance rgb_ module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "shape distortions"
msgid "correct lens distortions"
msgstr "distorsione delle forme"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "All lenses introduce some artifacts (distortion, chromatic aberrations, vignetting) to the image. The [_lens correction_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md) module can correct many of these issues for a wide variety of lenses. The [_chromatic aberrations_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md) and [_raw chromatic aberrations_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/raw-chromatic-aberrations.md) modules can also be used to handle chromatic aberrations for lenses that are not (or only partially) supported by _lens correction_. In most cases simply enabling the _lens correction_ module will auto-detect your lens and auto-apply all available corrections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you decide to use the _lens correction_ module, it should be enabled at the start of your edit, before you adjust exposure, since vignetting correction can alter the overall brightness of your image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "reduce noise / retain detail"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "At a pixel level there is a trade-off to be made between the retention of fine details and the reduction/removal of sensor noise. In most situations, a small amount of noise is perfectly acceptable and will not be noticeable except when you zoom in to 100%. At this scale you are not viewing the image at a realistic size -- even when represented on a large monitor or print, noise that is obvious at high zoom factors will be virtually invisible on the final image. However, some modules further along the image pipeline (especially those that increase local contrast) may end up exaggerating any noise that is present so, again, there are trade-offs to be made.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The first module you can use to manage this is [_demosaic_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/demosaic.md), which controls how the single-color (R, G or B) pixels in your Raw file are converted to image pixels combining all three colors. Each demosaic algorithm has its own trade-offs between retaining fine detail and reducing noise. The default demosaic algorithm (RCD) usually provides a reasonable compromise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Demosaic algorithms can only do so much to manage noise in your image. The [_denoise (profiled)_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/denoise-profiled.md) module is individually tuned for a number of common camera sensors and can be used to reduce or remove pixel noise. As with demosaic you should alter the settings until you are happy with the balance of denoising vs fine-detail reproduction. The default settings are usually sufficient.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "sharpness and local contrast"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A number of modules can be used to adjust the local contrast and sharpness of your image. Most of these modules aim to enhance the apparent contrast of edges and do not add \"real\" sharpness (they are not the same as lens deconvolution). You should take care when using these modules as most of them can introduce artifacts (such as halos) when settings are pushed too far:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "the [_contrast equalizer_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md) module allows you to adjust contrast, limiting the effect to certain feature sizes. For example you can use it to increase the contrast of fine details without impacting larger-scale objects, or vice versa\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "the [_diffuse or sharpen_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/diffuse.md) module offers a number of presets for sharpening, lens deblurring and the addition of local contrast\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "the [_local contrast_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/local-contrast.md) module provides a simpler interface for quickly adding local contrast to your images -- just enabling the module or selecting one of the presets is often all that is required\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "the [_sharpen_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/sharpen.md) module is intended to re-introduce sharpness that was removed by your camera's anti-alias filter (if present) and can be enabled by default in [preferences > processing](../../preferences-settings/processing.md). The methods listed above are usually preferred to this legacy module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As with the modules mentioned in the previous section, you should take care when adding contrast to small-scale objects -- an image viewed at 100% is not a realistic representation of your final edit and local contrast adjustments are usually better judged when zoomed out.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "reconstruct blown highlights"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "While a well-exposed image will make post-processing much easier, darktable provides some tools handle blown highlights, in some cases even reconstructing lost colors or structure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The [_highlight reconstruction_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md) module provides a very basic attempt to manage blown highlights. By default, if any color channel is clipped, this module will clip the other channels, making the pixel white -- this prevents darktable from showing unnatural colors in the highlights. However it can be altered to attempt to reconstruct the lightness or color using any un-clipped channels. While this can re-introduce some detail, beware of the unrealistic colors that can result.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A better alternative is to disable _highlight reconstruction_ and instead use the [_reconstruct tab on the filmic rgb module_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md#reconstruct). As with the _highlight reconstruction_ module, filmic is able to reconstruct detail based on unclipped channels. Where this is not possible, it can also blend blown highlights smoothly with the rest of the image or pull colors from adjacent pixels. When incorporating this step into your workflow, you should do it at the same time as other _filmic rgb_ edits, performing adjustments in each tab of the module in turn, from left to right.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "adjust angle and perspective"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The [_rotate and perspective_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-perspective.md) module can be used to adjust the angle of the image or to simulate the functionality of a tilt/shift lens by altering the perspective, making converging horizontal and/or vertical lines parallel (keystone correction). This latter technique is most commonly used for architectural photography. If you just want to correct the angle of the horizon you can do this by right-clicking and dragging along the horizon line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "remove spots and unwanted objects"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use the [_retouch_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md) module to remove unwanted objects by replacing pixels with detail from elsewhere in the image. This module also offers powerful techniques for removing large-scale objects (such as spots or blemishes) while leaving fine-scale details (like hairs and follicles) intact. The most common use for this module is to remove dust spots from images or blemishes from skin.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "remove atmospheric haze"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are two methods for removing atmospheric haze in darktable. The [haze removal](../../module-reference/processing-modules/haze-removal.md) module provides a much simpler interface, but the \"dehaze\" preset in the [_diffuse or sharpen_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/diffuse.md) module can provide more flexibility when needed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "exposure adjustment"
msgid "creative adjustments"
msgstr "correzione dell'esposizione"

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "crop and frame"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use the [_crop_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/crop.md) module to crop your image and the [_framing_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md) module to surround your image with a colored frame. Both modules can be set to use a predefined or custom aspect ratio -- for example, you could place a square-cropped image into a 3:2 frame.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "dodge and burn"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Dodging and burning is a traditional darkroom technique to add and remove brightness from an image. There are two recommended ways to achieve this\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you want to selectively dodge or burn only certain objects you can apply a [new instance](../../darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md) of the [_exposure_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md) module using a [drawn mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) to isolate the effect to the required area of the image (see also the [mask refinement](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/refinement-controls.md) section for more information). Move the exposure slider to alter the brightness of the masked area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you wish to dodge or burn areas with a similar brightness (for example, to brighten the shadows or darken the highlights) you should use the [_tone equalizer_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/tone-equalizer.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "convert to monochrome"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable provides a number of ways to remove the color from your image. The most flexible method is to use the [_gray tab of the color calibration module_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md#gray-tab). A number of film emulation presets are available in this module to provide you with a starting point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "See the [developing monochrome images](../../guides-tutorials/monochrome.md) section for details of other techniques.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color grading"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The [_color balance rgb_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md) module is your one-stop-shop for controlling the colors in your image. Adjustments can be isolated to the shadows, highlights and mid-tones, or applied at a global level.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "other important topics"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "re-use common module settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you find yourself using the same module parameters repeatedly, you can create [presets](../../darkroom/processing-modules/presets.md) containing your favorite settings. If you use the same settings on every image, you can also make presets apply automatically to new images. For example, you may find yourself adding the same exposure settings to every image taken by a certain camera -- in this case you can create a preset that automatically applies those corrections only to images from that camera.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You may also have groups of module settings that you commonly apply only to certain types of image. You can use [styles](../../module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/styles.md) to apply multiple module settings at once to a selection of images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "exposure adjustment"
msgid "perform adjustments locally"
msgstr "correzione dell'esposizione"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Most darktable modules can either be applied to the whole image, or restricted to parts of the image using [drawn and parametric masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "control darktable with other input methods"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/workflow/process.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You don't need to use the darktable UI to make adjustments to your images. Most of the functionality in darktable can also be controlled using shortcuts defined with your keyboard/mouse and even with other input devices such as game controllers and MIDI devices. See the [shortcuts](../../preferences-settings/shortcuts.md) section for details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/overview/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Overview"
msgstr "Panoramica"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "supported file formats"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable supports a huge number of file formats from various camera manufacturers. In addition darktable can read a wide range of low- and high-dynamic-range images -- mainly for data exchange between darktable and other software.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In order for darktable to consider a file for import, it must have one of the following extensions (case independent): `3FR, ARI, ARW, BAY, BMQ, CAP, CINE, CR2, CR3, CRW, CS1, DC2, DCR, DNG, GPR, ERF, FFF, EXR, IA, IIQ, JPEG, JPG, K25, KC2, KDC, MDC, MEF, MOS, MRW, NEF, NRW, ORF, PEF, PFM, PNG, PXN, QTK, RAF, RAW, RDC, RW1, RW2, SR2, SRF, SRW, STI, TIF, TIFF, X3F`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If darktable was compiled with JPEG2000 support, the following extensions are also recognized: `J2C, J2K, JP2, JPC`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If darktable was compiled with GraphicsMagick support, the following extensions are also recognized: `BMP, DCM, GIF, JNG, JPC, JP2, MIFF, MNG, PBM, PGM, PNM, PPM`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "camera raw files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable reads raw files using the open source library [RawSpeed](https://github.com/darktable-org/rawspeed), originally developed by Klaus Post and now maintained as part of the darktable project. The number of supported cameras and file formats is constantly increasing. Most modern camera models are supported, and new ones tend to get added very quickly. It is beyond the scope of this manual to give an exhaustive list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the exception of Fujifilm X-Trans cameras, darktable does not decode images from cameras with non-Bayer sensors (e.g. Sigma cameras with the Foveon X3 sensor).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "other image files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable natively reads “ordinary” images in JPEG, 8-bit/16-bit PNG and 8-bit/16-bit TIFF format, as well as 16-bit/32-bit floating point TIFF formats.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/overview/supported-file-formats.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable also reads high dynamic range images in OpenEXR, RGBE and PFM formats.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Preferences & Settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control the overall look and feel of darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interface language\n"
": Set the language of the user interface. The system default is marked with an * (needs a restart)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"theme\n"
": Set the theme for the user interface. Aside from any aesthetic considerations, the recommended interface color for color evaluation is middle gray. Visual perception is affected by ambient brightness, and a low user interface brightness causes all kinds of illusions. Using a dark interface to retouch photos can therefore lead to excessive retouching (abuse of contrast and saturation) and to a photo that is too dark when printed. It is therefore highly recommended that you use one of the \"gray\" themes for retouching work as these are designed so that the user interface approximates middle gray (default \"darktable\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"prefer performance over quality\n"
": Enable this option to render thumbnails and previews at a lower quality. This increases the rendering speed by a factor of 4, and is useful when working on slower computers (default off). This also improves the performance of slideshow image rendering.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"use system font size\n"
": Select this option to use the font size defined by your system. If unchecked, you may enter a custom font size in the box below (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"font size in points\n"
": If the \"use system font size\" option is switched off, enter a font size (in points) for darktable to use. The font size will be changed immediately.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GUI controls and text DPI\n"
": Adjust the global GUI resolution to rescale controls, buttons, labels, etc. Increase for a magnified GUI, decrease to fit more content in the window. Set to -1 to use the system-defined global resolution. The default is 96 DPI on most systems. (needs a restart)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "CSS Theme Modifications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In addition to selecting a pre-built theme you can also apply additional CSS customisations of your own to tweak the look-and-feel of darktable. A text box is provided for this purpose.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When you have finished entering your CSS tweaks, click on the 'save CSS and apply' button. This will save your CSS to a file (`$HOME/.config/darktable/user.css`) and immediately apply it to the current darktable session.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If your changes cause any issues, you can uncheck the \"modify selected theme with CSS tweaks below\" check box. This will immediately restore the base theme but will leave your tweaks in the editor so that you can re-edit them and try again. Simply press \"save CSS and apply\" again when you are ready to retry. This will automatically re-check the \"modify selected theme with CSS tweaks below\" checkbox and apply the new CSS.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you have any issues with darktable please retry with this option unchecked to be certain that they were not caused by any of your alterations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you want to understand how darktable themes are constructed you are advised to look at the file `$DARKTABLE/share/darktable/themes/darktable.css` for more information (where `$DARKTABLE` is darktable's installation directory). You can also use the Gtk Inspector tool to analyse the existing layout.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control default file naming conventions used when [importing](../module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md) images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "session options"
msgstr "Opzioni sessione"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following options define the default naming pattern for use in the \"copy & import\" or \"copy & import from camera\" options in the import module, or when taking photos in the [tethering](../tethering/_index.md) view.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The naming pattern consists of three parts: a base part defining the parent folder, a session part defining a sub directory (which is specific to the individual import session), and a file name part defining the filename structure for each imported image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Several pre-defined variables can be used in the pattern as placeholders:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$(HOME)              the home folder as defined by the system\n"
"$(PICTURES_FOLDER)   the pictures folder as defined by the system (usually “$HOME/Pictures”)\n"
"$(DESKTOP)           the desktop folder as defined by the system (usually “$HOME/Desktop”)\n"
"$(USERNAME)          your user account name on the system\n"
"$(FILE_NAME)         basename of the imported image\n"
"$(FILE_EXTENSION)    extension of the imported image\n"
"$(JOBCODE)           unique identifier of the import job\n"
"$(SEQUENCE)          a sequence number within the import job\n"
"$(MAX_WIDTH)         maximum image width to limit within export session\n"
"$(MAX_HEIGHT)        maximum image height to limit within export session\n"
"$(ID)                unique identification number of the image in darktable's database\n"
"$(YEAR)              year at the date of import\n"
"$(MONTH)             month at the date of import\n"
"$(DAY)               day at the date of import\n"
"$(HOUR)              hour at the time of import\n"
"$(MINUTE)            minute at the time of import\n"
"$(SECOND)            second at the time of import\n"
"$(EXIF_YEAR)         year the photo was taken (from Exif data)\n"
"$(EXIF_MONTH)        month the photo was taken (from Exif data)\n"
"$(EXIF_DAY)          day the photo was taken (from Exif data)\n"
"$(EXIF_HOUR)         hour the photo was taken (from Exif data)\n"
"$(EXIF_MINUTE)       minute the photo was taken (from Exif data)\n"
"$(EXIF_SECOND)       seconds the photo was taken (from Exif data)\n"
"$(EXIF_ISO)          ISO value of the photo (from Exif data)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"base directory naming pattern\n"
": The base directory part of the naming pattern (default `$(PICTURES_FOLDER)/Darktable`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"keep original filename\n"
": Check this box to keep original the filename instead of using the pattern below when importing from a camera or card (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file naming pattern\n"
": The file name part of the naming pattern (default `$(YEAR)$(MONTH)$(DAY)_$(SEQUENCE).$(FILE_EXTENSION`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control functionality in the [lighttable](../lighttable/_index.md) view and modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hide built-in presets for utility modules\n"
": If enabled, only user-defined presets will be shown in presets menu for utility modules -- built-in presets will be hidden (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"use single-click in the collections module\n"
": Enable \"single click\" mode in the [collections](../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/collections.md) module, which allows ranges to be selected (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"expand a single utility module at a time\n"
": Controls how utility modules are expanded. If this option is enabled, expanding a module by clicking collapses any other currently expanded panel. If you want to expand a panel without collapsing the others you can do so with Shift+click. Disabling this option inverts the meaning of click and Shift+click (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scroll to utility modules when expanded/collapsed\n"
": With this option enabled the side panels will scroll a utility module to the top of the panel when it is expanded or collapsed (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rating an image one star twice will not zero out the rating\n"
": Normally clicking a one star rating twice will set a zero star rating to that image. Check this option to disable this functionality (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show scrollbars for center view\n"
": Choose whether to show scrollbars in the center view of the lighttable (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"use raw file instead of embedded JPEG from size\n"
": When generating thumbnails for images that have not yet been processed in the darkroom, if the thumbnail size is greater than this value, generate it by processing the raw image data. If the thumbnail is below this size, use the JPEG preview image embedded in the raw file. Once an image has been processed in the darkroom, thumbnails will always be generated from raw data (you can revert back to the JPEG preview by discarding history). To render thumbnails with the best quality choose \"always\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"high quality processing from size\n"
": If the thumbnail size is greater than this value and is being generated from raw data, it will be processed using the full quality rendering path, which is better but slower (default 720p). To render thumbnails with the best quality, choose \"always\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"delimiters for size categories\n"
": Size categories are used to allow different thumbnail overlays to be shown depending on the thumbnail size. A pipe delimited set of values defines at what image sizes the category changes. The default value of \"120|400\" means that there will be 3 categories of thumbnail: 0-120px, 120-400px and >400px.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pattern for the thumbnail extended overlay text\n"
": If you have chosen to show extended overlay text over thumbnail images, this setting allows you to define what information is displayed. This pattern can use any of the variables defined in the [variables](../special-topics/variables.md) section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pattern for the thumbnail tooltip (empty to disable)\n"
": Defines what information is displayed in the tooltip when the mouse hovers over image thumbnails. This pattern can also use any of the variables defined in the [variables](../special-topics/variables.md) section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/lua-options.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lua options"
msgstr "Opzioni lua"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/lua-options.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lua scripts installer don't show again\n"
": Check this box to hide the [lua scripts installer](../module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/lua-scripts-installer.md) in the lighttable if no lua scripts are installed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/overview.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "darktable comes with a number of user-configurable preferences. These can be adjusted in the preferences dialog, which can be reached by clicking the gear icon on the right of the [top panel](../overview/user-interface/top-panel.md). Preferences are separated into tabs, each of which is described in more detail in the following sections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/overview.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When opened from within the lighttable or darkroom views, the appropriate tab will be loaded by default to allow you to modify that view's settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/overview.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Any altered settings (i.e. those that differ from their default state) are highlighted with a bullet beside them. If you change a setting that needs a restart to take effect, a message will appear as a reminder after you exit the preferences dialog.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/overview.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Double click on a setting's label to reset to its default value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/overview.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The preferences dialog can be closed by clicking on the close button in your window manager or pressing the Escape key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/presets.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This menu provides an overview of the [presets](../darkroom/processing-modules/presets.md) that are defined for darktable's modules, and allows you to modify some of their properties.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/presets.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Pre-defined presets (those that are included by default within darktable) are shown with a lock symbol. Their properties cannot be changed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/presets.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "User-defined presets can be imported from exported `.dtpreset` files using the \"import\" button at the bottom of the screen. You can export _all_ user-defined presets to a single directory using the \"export\" button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/presets.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Delete a user-defined preset by selecting it and pressing the Delete key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/presets.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Edit a user-defined preset's properties by selecting it and pressing Enter or double-clicking. This will open a dialog that allows the preset to be edited, exported to an external `.dtpreset` file or deleted. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/presets.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "See the [creating and editing presets](../darkroom/processing-modules/presets.md#creating-and-editing-presets) section for more information about the other properties that can be edited in this dialog.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "processing"
msgstr "elaborazione"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control how images are processed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "image processing"
msgstr "Elaborazione d'immagine"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"always use LittleCMS 2 to apply output color profile\n"
": If this option is activated, darktable will use the LittleCMS 2 system library to apply the output color profile instead of its own internal routines. This is significantly slower than the default but might give more accurate results in some cases. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": If the given ICC is LUT-based or contains both a LUT and a matrix, darktable will use LittleCMS 2 to render the colors regardless of this parameter's value (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pixel interpolator (warp)\n"
": The pixel interpolator used for rotation, lens correction, liquify, crop and final scaling.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Whenever we scale or distort an image we have to choose a pixel interpolation algorithm (see [wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_scaling) for details). For warping modules, darktable offers bilinear, bicubic or lanczos2. In general, bicubic is a safe option for most cases and is the default value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pixel interpolator (scaling)\n"
": The pixel interpolator used for scaling. The same options are provided as for the warp modules, but with the addition of lanczos3.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": lanczos3 can cause pixel overshoots leading to artefacts but sometimes gives a more crisp visual appearance. This option is therefore only provided for transforming (scaling) algorithms and is the default value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"3D lut root folder\n"
": Define the root folder (and sub-folders) containing Lut files used by the [_lut 3D_](../module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md) module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"auto-apply pixel workflow defaults\n"
": Choose which modules and module order to apply to new images by default:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_scene-referred_ workflow (default) assumes that most processing will be performed in a linear RGB color space. Selecting this option will automatically enable the [_filmic rgb_](../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md) and [_exposure_](../module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md) modules and will set the pixelpipe order to _v3.0_ which is the (scene-referred) order defined for darktable 3.0 and later. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "  The _exposure_ module will include an automatic adjustment of +0.5 EV to adjust the mid-gray to match that of the majority of SLR cameras. This adjustment can be overridden with an automatically-applied preset if the default produces consistently dark images for your camera. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "  Finally, this setting automatically enables the \"compensate camera exposure\" option in the _exposure_ module to adjust the global brightness appropriately in cases where the camera's exposure compensation dial was used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_display-referred_ workflow assumes that most processing will be performed in the Lab color space and is the legacy mode from darktable 2.6 and earlier. Selecting this option will automatically enable the [_base curve_](../module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md) module and set the pixelpipe order to the _legacy_ (display-referred) order used by default up to version 2.6.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_none_ will not enable any modules by default and will set the pixelpipe to the _v3.0_ (scene-referred) order defined for darktable 3.0 and later.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"auto-apply chromatic adaptation defaults\n"
": Choose which module is responsible for performing white balance adjustments (chromatic adaptation) by default. Select \"legacy\" (default) to perform basic chromatic adaptation within the [_white balance_](../module-reference/processing-modules/white-balance.md) module only. Select \"modern\" to use a combination of the _white balance_ and [_color calibration_](../module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md) modules to perform modern chromatic adaptation with improved color science. These settings are applied by default to new edits and will not impact old edits.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"auto-apply per camera basecurve presets\n"
": Use a per-camera base curve by default (if available) instead of the generic manufacturer one. This should only be used in conjunction with the _display-referred_ workflow defined above (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"auto-apply sharpen\n"
": Auto-apply the sharpen module to new images by default. This option is not recommended on cameras without a low-pass filter. (default on, requires a restart).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"detect monochrome previews\n"
": Enable this option to analyse images during import and tag them with the `darkroom|mode|monochrome` tag if they are found to be monochrome. The analysis is based on the preview image embedded within the imported file. This makes for a more convenient workflow when working with monochrome images, but it slows down the import, so this setting is disabled by default.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show warning messages\n"
": Enable this option to display warning messages in processing modules where non-standard and possibly harmful settings have been used in the pipeline. Such messages can sometimes be false-positives (because of intentional non-standard settings) and can be disregarded if you know what you are doing. Disable to hide these warnings. (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "cpu / gpu / memory"
msgstr "CPU / GPU / Memoria"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"memory in megabytes to use for thumbnail cache\n"
": In order to speed up the display of film rolls, darktable stores image thumbnails in a cache on disk (primary cache) and loads it into memory at startup. This setting controls the size of the cache in megabytes. Needs a restart if changed (default 512MB).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"enable disk backend for thumbnail cache\n"
": If activated, darktable stores all thumbnails on disk as a secondary cache, and thereby keeps thumbnails accessible if they are dropped from the primary cache. This needs more disk space but speeds up the [lighttable](../lighttable/_index.md) view as it avoids the reprocessing of thumbnails (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"enable disk backend for full preview cache\n"
": If enabled, darktable writes full preview images to disk (`.cache/darktable/`) when evicted from the memory cache. Note that this can take a lot of storage (several gigabytes for 20k images) and darktable will never delete cached images. It's safe to delete these manually if you want. Enabling this option will greatly improve lighttable performance when zooming an image in full preview mode (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"host memory limit (in MB) for tiling\n"
": In order to manage large images on systems with limited memory darktable does tile-wise processing. This variable controls the maximum amount of memory (in MB) a module may use during image processing. Lower values will force memory-hungry modules to process an image with increasing number of tiles. Setting this to 0 will omit any limits. Values below 500 will be treated as 500. Needs a restart if changed (default 1500).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"minimum amount of memory (in MB) for a single buffer in tiling\n"
": If set to a positive, non-zero value, this variable defines the minimum amount of memory (in MB) that darktable should take for a single tile. Needs a restart if changed (default 16).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"activate [OpenCL](../special-topics/opencl/_index.md) support\n"
": _darktable_ can use your GPU to significantly speed up processing. The OpenCL interface requires suitable hardware and matching OpenCL drivers on your system. If one of those is not found the option is grayed out. Can be switched on and off at any time and takes immediate effect (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/processing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"OpenCL scheduling profile\n"
": Defines how preview and full pixelpipe tasks are scheduled on OpenCL enabled systems: \n"
": - _default_: the GPU processes the center view pixelpipe; the CPU processes the preview pipe; \n"
": - _multiple GPUs_: both pixelpipes are processed in parallel on two different GPUs; \n"
": - _very fast GPU_: both pixelpipes are processed sequentially on the GPU. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "security"
msgstr "sicurezza"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control whether warning messages are shown before undertaking certain activities.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before removing images from the library\n"
": Always ask before removing an image from darktable's library database, where the image/xmp file is retained (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before deleting images from disk\n"
": Always ask before deleting an image file (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before discarding history stack\n"
": Always ask before discarding the history stack of an image (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"try to use trash when deleting images\n"
": Instead of physically deleting images from disk, attempt to put them into the system's trash bin (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before moving images from film roll folder\n"
": Always ask before moving an image file (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before copying images to new film roll folder\n"
": Always ask before copying an image file to a new location (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before removing empty folders\n"
": Always ask before removing any empty folder. This can happen after moving or deleting images (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before deleting a tag\n"
": Always ask before deleting a tag from an image (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before deleting a style\n"
": Always ask before deleting a style (default on). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before deleting a preset\n"
": Always ask before deleting a preset (default on). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ask before exporting in overwrite mode\n"
": Always ask before [exporting](../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/export.md) images in overwrite mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "other"
msgstr "altro"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"password storage backend to use\n"
": The backend to use for password storage. Options: “auto” (default), “none”, “libsecret”, “kwallet”. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"executable for playing audio files\n"
": Define an external program which is used in the lighttable view to play audio files that some cameras record to keep notes for images (default “aplay”). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "storage"
msgstr "archivio"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following options are related to darktable's library database and [XMP sidecar files](../overview/sidecar-files/_index.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "database"
msgstr "base dati"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"check for database maintenance\n"
": Indicates when darktable should check for database fragmentation and perform maintenance. Options are \"never\", \"on startup\", \"on close\" and \"on both\". Each of these is also available with an additional \"(don't ask)\" option to perform the checks automatically without prompting (default \"on close\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"database fragmentation ratio threshold\n"
": Fragmentation ratio (in per cent) above which database maintenance should be performed (subject to the selection made in the option above) (default 25).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"create database snapshot\n"
": Specifies how often darktable should create database snapshots. Options are \"never\", \"once a month\", \"once a week\", \"once a day\" and \"on close\" (default \"once a week\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"how many snapshots to keep\n"
": Number of snapshots to keep after creating a new snapshot, not counting database backups taken when moving between darktable versions. Enter \"-1\" to store an unlimited number of snapshots. (default 10)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "xmp"
msgstr "xmp"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"write sidecar file for each image\n"
": XMP files provide a redundant method of saving the changes that you have made to an image, in addition to the changes saved to darktable's database. This option allows you to choose when to write these files. Choose from:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _never_: Don't write XMP files. This can be useful if you are running multiple version of darktable for development/testing purposes but is not normally recommended\n"
": - _on import_: An XMP file will be written as soon as you add an image to darktable's library and will be subsequently updated each time you edit it\n"
": - _after edit_: An XMP file will be written the first time you perform an edit on an image and will be updated on each subsequent edit. Importing will not generate an XMP file by default.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": It's strongly recommended that you choose either \"on import\" or \"after edit\". XMP files provide a useful fail-safe so that you don't lose data if your database becomes corrupted. Backing up your raw file plus the accompanying XMP file will allow you to fully restore your work at a later date by re-importing your edit history back into darktable (default \"on import\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"store xmp tags in compressed format\n"
": Entries in XMP tags can get rather large and may exceed the available space to store the history stack in some output files on export. This option allows binary XMP tags to be compressed in order to save space. Available options are “never”, “always”, and “only large entries” (default).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/storage.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"look for updated xmp files on startup\n"
": Scan all XMP files on startup and check if any have been updated in the meantime by some other software. If updated XMP files are found, a menu is opened for the user to choose which of the XMP files to reload (replacing darktable's database entries by the XMP file contents) and which of the XMP to overwrite from darktable's database. Activating this option also causes darktable to check for text sidecar files that have been added after import time (default off). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Control functionality in the [darkroom](../darkroom/_index.md) view and associated modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pen pressure control for brush masks\n"
": Controls how the pressure reading of a graphics tablet impacts newly generated [drawn mask](../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) brush strokes. You can control the brush width, hardness and opacity. “Absolute” control means that the pressure reading directly defines the attribute with a value between 0% and 100%. “Relative” means that the pressure reading adjusts the attribute between zero and the pre-defined default value (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"smoothing of brush strokes\n"
": Sets the level for smoothing of [drawn mask](../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) brush strokes. Stronger smoothing leads to fewer nodes and easier editing at the expense of lower accuracy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scroll down to increase mask parameters\n"
": By default, scrolling your mouse up increases the value of the relevant shape parameters in [drawn masks](../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md). Set this preference to reverse the behavior (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pattern for the image information line\n"
": Set the information to be displayed in the [image information line](../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/image-info-line.md). You can use any variables in the [variables](../special-topics/variables.md) section as well as `$(NL)` for a new line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"position of the image information line\n"
": Choose the darkroom panel in which the [image information line](../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/image-info-line.md) is displayed. Choose between “top left” “top right” “top center” “bottom” and “hidden” (default \"bottom\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"border around image in darkroom mode\n"
": Display the center image in darkroom mode with an outside border of the given number of pixels (default 20). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show scrollbars for center view\n"
": Choose whether to show scrollbars in the center view of the darkroom (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"demosaicing for zoomed out darkroom mode\n"
": Choose how to demosaic images in the darkroom view when not viewing the image at 1:1 zoom scale. Note: this setting is only used for interactive work and does not affect exported images.\n"
": - _always bilinear (fast)_ is fastest, but not as sharp\n"
": - _at most RCD (reasonable)_ uses RCD + interpolation modes. X-Trans sensors will use VNG as the middle-ground setting.\n"
": - _full (possibly slow)_ will use the settings from the [_demosaic_](../module-reference/processing-modules/demosaic.md) module.\n"
": (default \"_at most RCD (reasonable)_\"). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"reduce resolution of preview image\n"
": Reduce the resolution of the [navigation preview](../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/navigation.md) image (choose from \"original\", \"1/2\", \"1/3\" or \"1/4\" size). This may improve the speed of the rendering but take care as it can also hinder accurate color-picking and masking (default \"original\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show loading screen between images\n"
": Show gray loading screen when navigating between images in the darkroom. Switch this option off to just show a simple toast message and leave the previous image in place until the next image is loaded. Note that switching this option off can be very useful to quickly compare duplicate images, however, there might be issues with long loading times (leading you to think the next image has already loaded) and you may observe visual artifacts while the next image is loading (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "modules"
msgstr "moduli"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"display of individual color channels\n"
": Control how individual color channels are displayed when activated in the [parametric masks](../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) feature. You can choose between “false color” and “gray scale” (default \"false color\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hide built-in presets for processing modules\n"
": If enabled, only user-defined presets will be shown in the presets menu for processing modules -- built-in presets will be hidden (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"expand a single processing module at a time\n"
": Control how [processing modules](../module-reference/processing-modules) are expanded in the darkroom. If this option is enabled, expanding a module by clicking collapses any currently expanded module. If you want to expand a module without collapsing the others you can do so with Shift+click. Disabling this option inverts the meaning of click and Shift+click (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"only collapse modules in current group\n"
": When choosing to expand a single processing module at a time (using the logic defined in the previous setting), only collapse other modules that appear in the current visible group. Disable this option to ensure that modules in non-visible groups are also collapsed (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"expand the module when it is activated, and collapse it when disabled\n"
": Select this option for the darkroom to automatically expand or collapse [processing modules](../module-reference/processing-modules) when they are enabled or disabled. (default off)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scroll to processing modules when expanded/collapsed\n"
": With this option enabled [processing modules](../module-reference/processing-modules) are scrolled to the top of the right-hand panel when expanded or collapsed (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"white balance slider colors\n"
": Controls the appearance of the temperature/tint sliders in the [white balance](../module-reference/processing-modules/white-balance.md) module.\n"
": - _no color_: background of the sliders is not colored at all.\n"
": - _illuminant color_: slider colors represent the color of the light source, i.e. the color you are adjusting to in order to achieve neutral white\n"
": - _effect emulation_: slider colors represent the effect the adjustment would have had on the scene. This is how most other raw processors show temperature/tint sliders colors.\n"
": (default _no color_)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"colorbalance slider block layout\n"
": Controls the appearance of the shadows/mid-tones/highlights sections in the [color balance](../module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance.md) module.\n"
": - _list_: all sliders are shown in one long list (with headers)\n"
": - _tabs_: use tabs to switch between the blocks of sliders\n"
": - _columns_: the blocks of sliders are shown next to each other (in narrow columns)\n"
": (default _list_)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show right-side buttons in processing module headers\n"
": Choose whether to show the four buttons (mask indicator, multi-instance menu, reset, presets menu) on the right-hand-side of the [module header](../darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md) for processing modules. These buttons will always appear when the mouse is over the module. At other times they will be shown or hidden according to this preference selection: \n"
": - _always_: always show all buttons\n"
": - _active_: only show the buttons when the mouse is over the module\n"
": - _dim_: buttons are dimmed when mouse is not over the module\n"
": - _auto_: hide the buttons when the panel is narrow\n"
": - _fade_: fade out all buttons when the panel narrows\n"
": - _fit_: hide all the buttons if the module name doesn't fit\n"
": - _smooth_: fade out all buttons in one header simultaneously\n"
": - _glide_: gradually hide individual buttons as needed\n"
": (default _always_)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show mask indicator in module headers\n"
": If enabled, an icon will be shown in the header of any processing modules that have a [mask](../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md) applied (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"prompt for name on addition of new instance\n"
": If enabled, when creating a new instance of a processing module, a prompt will be immediately displayed allowing you to set a name for the new instance (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "miscellaneous"
msgstr "altro"

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "interface"
msgstr "interfaccia"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sort built-in presets first\n"
": Choose how the presets menu is sorted. If this option is enabled, built-in presets are shown first. If the option is disabled, user presets are shown first (default on).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mouse wheel scrolls modules side panel by default\n"
": When enabled, the mouse wheel scrolls side panels by default and Ctrl+Alt+wheel scrolls data entry fields. When disabled, this behavior is reversed (default off). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"always show panels' scrollbars\n"
": Defines whether the panel scrollbars should be always visible or activated only depending on the panel content (default on). (needs a restart) \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"position of the scopes module\n"
": Choose whether to show the [scopes](../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/scopes.md) module in the left or right panel (default right). (needs a restart)\n"
msgstr ""
"posizione del modulo scopi\n"
": Scegli dove mostrare il modulo [scopes](../module-reference/"
"utility-modules/shared/scopes.md) sul pannello di sinistra o di destra (in "
"modo predefinito a destra). (richiede un riavvio)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"method to use for getting the display profile\n"
": This option allows the user to force darktable to use a specific method to obtain the current display profile for [color management](../special-topics/color-management/_index.md). In the default setting “all”, darktable will choose to query the X display server's xatom or the colord system service. You can set this option to “xatom” or “colord” to enforce a specific method if the two methods give different results. You can run the [darktable-cmstest](../special-topics/program-invocation/darktable-cmstest.md) binary to examine your color management subsystem.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "tags"
msgstr "etichette"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"omit hierarchy in simple tag lists\n"
": When exporting images any hierarchical tags are also added as a simple list of non-hierarchical tags to make them visible to some other programs. When this option is checked darktable will only include the last part of the hierarchy and ignore the rest. So `foo|bar|baz` will only add `baz`. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"disable the entry completion\n"
": The entry completion is useful for those who enter tags using the keyboard only. For others the entry completion can be embarrassing (default off). (needs a restart) \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "keyboard shortcuts with multiple instances"
msgstr "Scorciatoie da tastiera con istanze multiple"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is possible to create multiple instances of many processing modules. In this scenario it is not always obvious which instance should be controlled by keyboard shortcut operations. The following options control rules that are applied (in order) to decide which module instance keyboard shortcuts should be applied to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "These rules are also used when clicking and dragging on the scopes module to change exposure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"prefer expanded instances\n"
": If instances of the module are expanded, ignore collapsed instances (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"prefer enabled instances\n"
": After applying the above rule, if remaining instances of the module are active, ignore inactive instances (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"prefer unmasked instances\n"
": After applying the above rules, if remaining instances of the module are unmasked, ignore masked instances (default off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"selection order\n"
": After applying the above rules, apply the shortcut to the first or last instance remaining (default \"last instance\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "map / geolocalisation view"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pretty print the image location\n"
": Show a more readable representation of the geo-location in the [image information](../module-reference/utility-modules/shared/image-information.md) module (default on). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "slideshow view"
msgstr "Vista presentazione"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"waiting time before each picture in slideshow\n"
": The number of seconds before displaying the next image (default 5) in the [slideshow view](../slideshow/_index.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "shortcuts"
msgstr "scorciatoie"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can perform almost any action in darktable with a keyboard/mouse shortcut. You can also use various other input devices, including MIDI devices and game controllers -- see the [midi device support](../special-topics/midi-device-support.md) section for details. These are referred to as _external devices_ or just _devices_ in this guide.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "defining shortcuts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A _shortcut_ is a combination of key or button presses and/or mouse or device movements that performs an _action_ in darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A single action may have multiple shortcuts but a single shortcut can only be linked to one action in a given darktable view -- you can't chain actions together except by applying a preset or style. You can, however, set up a single shortcut that does one thing in the lighttable view, say, and another in the darkroom view.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "initiating a shortcut"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A shortcut must be initiated by either\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "pressing a key on the keyboard; or\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "pressing a button or moving a knob/joystick on an external device \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You cannot initiate a shortcut by moving your mouse or pressing one of its buttons, as these actions are used to interact with darktable's UI.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "simple shortcuts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A shortcut that only includes button and/or key presses (and not mouse/device movements) is referred to as a _simple_ shortcut.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A simple shortcut must be initiated as above, but can include:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "One or more modifier keys (Shift, Ctrl, Alt), held down while executing the remainder of the shortcut\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Up to three key presses, the last one of which may be a long-press (defined as a key-press longer than your system's double-click duration)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Similarly, up to three device-button presses or mouse-button clicks, the last of which may be long\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Various combinations of keyboard, mouse, and device buttons can be used to create simple shortcuts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "creating additional modifiers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The only valid modifiers are the Shift, Ctrl and Alt keys on the keyboard. You can define additional keys (or device buttons) as modifiers by assigning keys/buttons to the the \"global/modifier\" action. However, these will merely function as extra Ctrl, Alt or Shift keys -- you cannot create \"new\" modifiers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "extending simple shortcuts with movement"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For certain actions you can choose to _extend_ a simple shortcut using mouse/device movement. For example you might hold Ctrl+X while scrolling with your mouse to change the value of a slider. The following can be used to extend a simple shortcut:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Movement of the mouse scroll wheel\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Horizontal, vertical or diagonal movement of the mouse cursor\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Movement of a knob/joystick on an external device\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To extend a simple shortcut, you must hold the final key/button of the simple shortcut while performing the extending mouse/device movement. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For external devices you do not need to start with a _simple_ shortcut -- you can directly assign a control knob or joystick to an action -- though this will significantly reduce the flexibility of such devices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Long button and key presses cannot be extended, as the length of the click/press is timed using the release of the final button/key -- such shortcuts must be terminated with the raising of the final button/key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** You may need to switch off the \"disable touchpad while typing\" setting if you want to use extended shortcuts with a laptop touchpad.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "actions"
msgstr "azioni"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Shortcuts are used to initiate _actions_ within darktable. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "An _action_ is usually (but not always) an operation that you might undertake using darktable's point-and-click user interface. For example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Increase, decrease or reset sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Scroll through dropdown lists\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enable, expand or focus modules\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click buttons\n"
msgstr "Clicca pulsanti\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Switch between views\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Such point-and-click type _actions_ are normally defined as the application of an _effect_ to an _element_ of a _widget_, where these terms are defined as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"widget\n"
": Each visible part of the user interface is known as a _widget_. For example the darktable application window is a widget, containing side panel widgets, each of which contains module widgets, each of which contains button, slider and dropdown list widgets etc... When assigning a shortcut to an action, you must first decide which widget it is to be applied to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"element\n"
": An _element_ is the part of a UI widget that is affected by your shortcut. For example, for a slider that has a color picker, you can make a shortcut activate the color picker _button_ element or change the _value_ element of the slider. For a row of tabs (the row is a single widget) you can select which tab element to activate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"effect\n"
": A shortcut can sometimes have multiple possible _effects_ on a given _element_. For example, a button can be activated as if it was pressed with a plain mouse-click or as if it was pressed with Ctrl+click. A slider's value can be edited, increased/decreased or reset.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "assigning shortcuts to actions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are two primary methods of assigning a shortcut to an action.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "visual shortcut mapping"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the ![visual mapping button](./shortcuts/visual-mapping-button.png#icon) icon in the [top panel](../overview/user-interface/top-panel.md) of any darktable view to enter visual shortcut mapping mode. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The mouse cursor will change as you hover over UI widgets, to indicate whether or not a mapping can be created:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A down arrow with a line ![expand icon](./shortcuts/expand-icon.png#icon) appears when you hover over a module header, to indicate that you can click to expand the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A spiral ![spiral icon](./shortcuts/spiral-icon.png#icon) indicates that a shortcut can be defined for the widget under the cursor. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "An up arrow ![up icon](./shortcuts/up-icon.png#icon) indicates that, in addition to assigning a shortcut, you can also add the widget to the [quick access panel](../darkroom/organization/quick-access-panel.md) in the darkroom (by Ctrl+clicking on it).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A down arrow ![down icon](./shortcuts/down-icon.png#icon) indicates that the widget is already in the quick access panel (Ctrl+click to remove it).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A cross ![cross icon](./shortcuts/cross-icon.png#icon) indicates that there is no mappable widget under the cursor. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Press a key combination while hovering over a mappable widget to assign a shortcut to that widget -- a default action will be assigned to that shortcut based on the type of widget and whether you have keyed a _simple_ or _extended_ shortcut.  See below for details of some of the default assigned actions. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Left-click on a mappable widget to open the shortcut mapping screen for that widget (see below). Left-click anywhere else on the screen to open the shortcut mapping screen, expanded (where possible) based on the part of the screen you have clicked on. This screen can be used to alter the action assigned to a shortcut and to configure shortcuts for non-visual actions. Entering the shortcut mapping screen exits visual shortcut mapping mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can assign as many shortcuts as you like in a single mapping session and then exit mapping mode when you are finished by clicking the ![visual mapping button](./shortcuts/visual-mapping-button.png#icon) icon again or right-clicking anywhere on the screen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can delete a user-defined shortcut mapping by defining it a second time against the same widget. If you attempt to reallocate an existing shortcut to a new action, you will be notified of the conflict and asked whether you wish to replace the existing shortcut.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "shortcut mapping screen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The most flexible way to create shortcuts is by using the shortcut mapping screen, which can be accessed from the global preferences dialog or by left-clicking in visual mapping mode. This screen allows access to all available actions, including some that are not directly linked to a UI widget.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The top panel of the shortcut mapping screen shows a list of available UI widgets/actions and the bottom panel shows the shortcuts currently assigned to them. You can search the top and bottom panels using the text entry boxes at the bottom of the screen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Double-click an item in the top panel to create a new shortcut for that item, and then enter your desired shortcut (right-click to cancel). Once you have done this, a new entry will appear in the bottom panel showing the shortcut you have created. You can then manually alter the _element_, _effect_, _speed_ or _instance_ of the assigned action against that shortcut in the bottom panel. To delete a user-defined shortcut, select it in the bottom panel and press the Delete key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following additional options are provided in the shortcut mapping screen:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"export...\n"
": Export the current shortcut mappings for one or all of your devices (keyboard/mouse, midi, game) to an external file. The dialog will show you how many shortcuts exist for each device.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"import...\n"
": Import shortcut mappings from an external file for one or all of your devices. When loading a device, you can chose to assign it a different number. This can for example be used to exchange midi layouts. Before loading, you can chose to wipe the specific device first. When loading all from an empty file, this will effectively delete all your shortcuts. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"restore...\n"
": Restore your shortcut mappings to (a) The mappings shipped with darktable by default, (b) The start of your current session, or (c) The point at which the shortcut mapping screen was last opened. When restoring, you can choose to leave any additional shortcuts that were added after the relevant checkpoint as they are, so that only changed shortcuts are restored to their previous meaning. Or you can choose to first clear all shortcuts and just load the restore point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "deleting default shortcuts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is not currently possible to delete system-defined default shortcuts -- if you delete a default shortcut it will be automatically reinstated the next time you restart darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As a workaround, you can _override_ the default by assigning an identical shortcut to the \"global/no-op\" action (which does nothing). You can do this either in the shortcut mapping screen (above) or by directly editing your `$HOME/.config/darktable/shortcutsrc` file. If you want to disable a lot of default shortcuts the latter option is recommended (you must exit darktable first). For example, the following default shortcuts are defined in `shortcutsrc` for switching views in darktable:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"d=global/switch views/darkroom\n"
"l=global/switch views/lighttable\n"
"m=global/switch views/map\n"
"p=global/switch views/print\n"
"s=global/switch views/slideshow\n"
"t=global/switch views/tethering\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can disable all of these shortcuts by changing `shortcutsrc` as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"d=global/no-op\n"
"l=global/no-op\n"
"m=global/no-op\n"
"p=global/no-op\n"
"s=global/no-op\n"
"t=global/no-op\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "collections"
msgid "common actions"
msgstr "raccolte"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following is a list of some of the actions to which you can assign shortcuts, organized by widget type. This is not an exhaustive list and you are encouraged to browse the shortcut mapping screen for a complete list of available actions. If you assign a shortcut to a widget, it will be given a default action, depending on the type of widget and on whether you have assigned a simple or extended shortcut.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Note that it is possible to assign a number of actions that have no effect. For example, all sliders include a _button_ element, regardless of whether such a button is actually present alongside a given slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "global"
msgstr "globale"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Actions in the \"global\" section of the shortcut mapping screen can be executed from any darktable view. Most of these actions do not have specific _elements_ as they are used to perform one-off operations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Actions in the \"views\" section can only be executed from the specified darktable view. As with global actions, most do not have specific _elements_ as they are used to perform one-off operations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "buttons "
msgstr "Pulsanti "

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A button is a clickable icon in the darktable interface. The default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to a _button_, is to activate that button as if clicked with the left mouse button. You can modify this action to activate the button as if clicked while holding a modifier key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "toggles"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A toggle is a button that has a persistent on/off state. It therefore has additional _effects_ to allow you to toggle it or explicitly set its state. As with a normal button the default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to a toggle, is to activate the toggle as if clicked with the left mouse button (which toggles the button on/off).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "All utility modules have the following elements:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_show_\n"
": Acts as a _toggle_ that expands and collapses the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_reset_\n"
": Acts as a _button_ that resets all module parameters when activated. The _ctrl-activate_ action can be used to re-apply any automatic presets for that module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_presets_\n"
": Allows you to select actions from the [presets](../darkroom/processing-modules/presets.md) menu (e.g. edit, update, previous, next). The default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to a _preset_ element, is to display a list of the available presets for selection. Extended shortcuts are not currently available for preset elements.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to a utility module, is to _toggle_ the _show_ element (expand/collapse the module).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In addition, shortcuts are available for all of the controls on each module as well as any stored presets (see below).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Processing modules have the same elements and defaults as utility modules with the following additional elements:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_enable_\n"
": Acts as a _toggle_ that switches the module on and off.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_focus_\n"
": Acts as a _toggle_ that focuses or defocuses the module. This is useful for modules such as [_crop_](../module-reference/processing-modules/crop.md) or [_tone equalizer_](../module-reference/processing-modules/tone-equalizer.md), whose on-screen controls are only activated when those modules have focus. For _crop_, changes are saved only when the module loses focus.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_instance_\n"
": Allows you to select actions from the [multiple-instance](../darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md) menu (e.g. move up/down, create new instance). The default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to the _instance_ element, is to display a list of the available options for selection; An extended shortcut will move the _preferred module instance_ (see below) up and down the pixelpipe.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If an action affects a processing module that can have multiple instances, you can choose which instance to adjust with a given shortcut. By default, all actions will affect the \"preferred\" instance, as defined using the settings in [preferences > miscellaneous > keyboard shortcuts with multiple instances](./miscellaneous.md#keyboard-shortcuts-with-multiple-instances).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "dropdowns"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A dropdown is a multi-selection box and has the following elements available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_selection_\n"
": Allows values to be selected from the dropdown list in various ways. The default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to a dropdown, is to display a popup _edit_ box with a list of the available values for selection; An extended shortcut (including a mouse movement) will scroll through the available values. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_button_\n"
": A standard _button_ element that allows the button to the right of the dropdown (if present) to be activated. For example, the _aspect_ dropdown in the [_crop_](../module-reference/processing-modules/crop.md) module has a button that allows the crop controls to be changed from portrait to landscape and vice versa.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A slider allows you to continuously alter an integer or decimal value, and has the following elements available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_value_\n"
": Allows the current value of the slider to be altered. The default action, when assigning a simple shortcut to a slider, is to display a popup _edit_ box so you can enter a value; An extended shortcut (including a mouse movement) will change the value up and down.  Value elements are also used for modifying some on-screen graphs. When modifying the _value_ element with a shortcut you may not exceed the bounds set in the visual slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_force_\n"
": This is the same as the _value_ element described above, but it allows you to exceed the bounds set in the visual slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_zoom_\n"
": Allows you to change the upper and lower bounds of the visual slider without altering the current value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"_button_\n"
": A standard _button_ element that allows the button to the right of the slider (if present) to be activated. For example, a slider may include a color picker to visually set its value based on selected elements of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can alter the value of a slider more quickly or slowly than normal by defining the _speed_ of the action in the shortcut mapping screen. By default a _value_ (or _force_) effect is given a speed of 1.0, which means that it is changed at the default rate defined by the given slider. You can alter the slider more quickly by increasing the speed (a speed of 10 makes the action 10x faster) or more slowly by decreasing it (a speed of 0.1 makes the action 10x slower).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "fallbacks"
msgstr "Abbandonate"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Where a _widget_ can have multiple different _actions_ applied to it, it can be tedious to set up individual shortcuts for each one of those actions. To make this process simpler, if you create a simple shortcut a number of effects can be made available by default as extensions to that shortcut. These are known as _fallbacks_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "While fallbacks are a powerful way to quickly set up multiple actions using predefined and consistent shortcuts, they will assign a lot of actions automatically (which might not be what you want), and can be hard to understand. Fallbacks are therefore disabled by default and you will need to click on the \"enable fallbacks\" check box in the shortcuts setup window to enable them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To take a brief example, you could create a simple shortcut (e.g. Ctrl+R) against a processing module. This will automatically set up the following _fallback_ effects using the defined shortcut, extended with mouse-clicks. In each case (except the first) you should hold the initial shortcut while clicking with your mouse. The final mouse-click will apply the action defined below:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+R (no mouse-click) to show/hide the module (the default fallback)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+R+left-click to enable/disable the module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+R+left-double-click to reset the module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/preferences-settings/shortcuts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+R+right-click to show the module's preset menu\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
